# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-aspen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-aspen/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The **AMC Hornet** is a compact automobile manufactured and marketed by American Motors Corporation (AMC) from 1970 through 1977 model years, in two- and four-door sedan, station wagon, and hatchback coupe configurations.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet replaced the compact Rambler American line, marking the end of the Rambler marque in the United States and Canadian markets.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet became significant for AMC in not only being a top seller during its production, but also a car platform serving the company in varying forms through the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Introduced in late 1969, AMC quickly earned a high rate of return for its development investment for the Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The platform became the basis for AMC's subcompact Gremlin, luxury compact Concord, liftback and sedan Spirit, and the innovative all-wheel drive AMC Eagle.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Its design would also outlast domestic competitors' compact platforms, including the Chevrolet Nova, Ford Maverick, and Plymouth Valiant.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The AMC Hornet also served as an experimental platform for alternative fuel and other automotive technologies.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Hornets were campaigned at various motorsports events with some corporate support.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A hatchback model also starred in an exceptional stunt jump in the 1974 James Bond film *The Man with the Golden Gun*.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Hornets were marketed in foreign markets and were assembled under license agreements between AMC and local manufacturers—for example, with Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM), Australian Motor Industries (AMI), and Toyota S.A.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Hudson Motor Car Company introduced the first Hornet in 1951 as a performance model featuring the automaker's new "H-145" engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The automaker formed a stock car racing team centered on the car, and the "Fabulous Hudson Hornet" soon became famous for its wins and stock-car title sweeps between 1951 and 1954.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Hornets "dominated stock car racing in the early-1950s, when stock car racers actually drove regular production stock cars." The Hudson Hornet car inspired Paul Newman's Doc Hudson movie character.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors retained rights to the "Hornet" name during the Automobile Manufacturers Association (AMA) resolution on factory-supported racing from 1957 until 1962.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This was initiated by the AMA to limit the auto industry's horsepower race and corporate sponsorship of racing to glamorize speed or performance.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Thus, the Hornet was dormant from 1958 until 1969 when AMC introduced a new compact car line for the 1970 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet name has since become steeped in history, not only for being a motorsport legend that was later immortalized in movies, but also because it was a "game changer" for AMC as the compact-size Hornet platform became the base for new market segments.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The rights to the "Hornet" nameplate were then transferred to Chrysler with the larger automaker's acquisition of AMC in 1987.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The nameplate has been on several concept cars since then.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet nameplate was reintroduced for the 2023 model year as a compact SUV marketed under the Dodge brand.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The AMC Hornet emerged as a pivotal vehicle in AMC's strategy, directly replacing the venerable Rambler American.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet's styling was foreshadowed by a pair of 1966 show cars, the four-door AMC Cavalier and the two-door Vixen.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The rising tide of imported cars had captured a significant portion of the U.S. market.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Development of the new model took AMC three years, a million person-hours, and US$40 million.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] An all-new robust front suspension with anti-brake dive was developed for AMC's large-sized "senior" 1970 models, and instead of developing lighter components for the new compact-size platform, the same parts were incorporated into the Hornet, demonstrating an engineering efficiency.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The chassis and sheet metal were entirely new, with the conventional front-engine rear-drive drivetrain carried over from the previous Rambler American.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet's 108-inch (2,743 mm) wheelbase platform was 2 inches (51 mm) longer than its predecessor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The design incorporated AMC's numerous innovative features and groundbreaking ideas.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The AMC Hornet was the first U.S.-made automobile to feature guardrail beam doors to protect occupants in the event of a side impact.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The compact-sized Hornet continued AMC's role as a "niche" marketer specializing in small cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was the first car in a line of new models that AMC would introduce over the following three years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet set the tone for what designer Dick Teague and chief executive officer Roy D.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Chapin Jr. had had in mind for the company in the 1970s.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The platform ultimately evolved into the innovative four-wheel-drive AMC Eagle, produced through 1988.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] With its manufacturer's suggested retail price (MSRP) of $1,994 for the base two-door model, the 1970 Hornet was a low-priced, economical small family car providing "cut-above interior appointments.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The base version 1970 Ford Maverick was listed at $1 more while the Chevrolet Nova and Plymouth Duster were priced 10% higher.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet and the Maverick were designed to stem the tide of imported cars that had captured 10% of the total U.S. market, with 80% of them retailing under $2,000.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] While domestic cars had generally grown larger, heavier, more fuel-consumptive, and more profitable through options, the rise of economical foreign vehicles highlighted a market segment where American offerings had largely abandoned the under-$2,000 price point.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Of the original eleven compact car nameplates, only four still qualified as compact-sized by 1969, and only one, the Rambler American, was priced under $2,000.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was initially available in a choice of two economical straight-six engines or a potent 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was offered as a two-door and four-door notchback sedan in its introductory year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The station wagon and two-door hardtop (no "B" pillar) body styles which had been available in the predecessor Rambler American line, were not carried over for the Hornet's initial launch.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In April 1970, a mid-model year introduction used the Hornet as the basis for the 96-inch (2,438 mm) wheelbase AMC Gremlin, which utilized the front half of the two-door Hornet's body and a truncated rear section with a window hatchback.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A four-door station wagon variant named the "Sportabout" was added to the 1971 lineup.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It featured a steeply raked hatchback rather than a conventional station wagon design with a rear window retracting into a drop-down tailgate.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors was careful not to describe the new body style as a traditional station wagon.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A unique SC/360 model was added for the 1971 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Available only as a two-door sedan, it included AMC's 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engine as standard, making it a compact-sized muscle car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] For the 1973 model year, a semi-fastback hatchback coupe with fold-down rear seats was also added to the lineup.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In 1973, a Levi's Jeans trim package was added based on the famous jeans manufacturer.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Levi's trim package was popular and was available for several years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet station wagon version was offered for two model years with a luxury trim package designed by Italian fashion designer Dr.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It is notable for being one of the first American cars to offer an upscale fashion "designer" trim level.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Introduced in September 1969, the first-year Hornets came in "base" and higher trim **SST** models, in two- and four-door sedan body styles.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was promoted as "the little rich car" with room for five passengers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The base model two-door sedan was $1,994, with the four-door an additional $78.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The base Hornets "were nicely trimmed for the price" with standard armrests, ashtrays, interior lights, glove box, cigarette lighter, coat hooks, and an integrated dash ventilation system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The SST was available with two-tone paint, a black, white, or blue vinyl covered roof, as well as individually adjustable reclining front seats in upholstered in custom fabric with matching side trim and door panels.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 199 cu in (3.3 L) straight-6 engine with a one-barrel carburetor rated at 128 hp (95 kW; 130 PS) at 4400 rpm and 182 lb⋅ft (247 N⋅m) of torque at 1600 rpm was standard on base trim models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The SST versions included the one-barrel 232 cu in (3.8 L) engine producing 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) at 4300 rpm and 215 lb⋅ft (292 N⋅m) of torque at 1600 rpm.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A two-barrel version of this engine was optional on both models increasing output by 10 hp (7 kW; 10 PS) and 7 lb⋅ft (9.5 N⋅m).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The standard transmission was the column-shifted three-speed manual with the one-barrel I6 engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Optional was the three-speed automatic and required with the two-barrel 232 cu in (3.8 L).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Optional on SST models was the 304 cu in (5.0 L) two-barrel V8 engine rated at 210 hp (157 kW; 213 PS) at 4400 rpm and 305 lb⋅ft (414 N⋅m) of torque at 2800 rpm.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 1971 model year was the introduction of the **Sportabout**, a 4-door wagon using a steeply sloped back design with a single liftgate-type hatch.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The styling was well-executed to appear muscular and purposeful while the liftgate-type station wagon appeared revolutionary in an era of traditional and upright rear tailgates.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] All featured a "Sportabout" emblem at the rear of the bodysides.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The two- and four-door sedans were carryovers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 engine became the standard across the range.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A marketing promotion in the Spring made available a new fabric folding sunroof on specially equipped Hornets, as well as on the Gremlin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The opening roof feature was included with the purchase of whitewall tires, custom wheel covers, pinstripes or rally stripes, a light group, and a special visibility group.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The **SC/360** was added for the 1971 model year as a compact 2-door muscle car that was intended as a follow-up to the 1969 SC Rambler.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The tire pressure sticker on the initial production of 1970 models hinted at the availability of the 360 V8 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The standard engine for the SC/360 was AMC's 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The SC/360 was distinguished by styled wheels, body striping, individual fully reclining front seats as well as other performance and appearance upgrades.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In standard form, with a two-barrel carburetor, the 360 produced 245 hp (183 kW; 248 PS) (gross) and the car was priced at just US$2,663 (about $40 below the 1971 Plymouth Duster 340).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This combination was offered by AMC to achieve a 12.5:1 weight-to-horsepower ratio for insurance rate calculations.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] With the addition of the $199 "Go" package's four-barrel carburetor and ram-air induction, the SC's power increased to 285 hp (213 kW; 289 PS).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Optional in place of the standard three-speed was a Hurst-shifted GM Borg-Warner Super T10 four-speed or an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Goodyear Polyglas D70x14 blackwall tires were standard, with upgrades including white lettered tires, a heavy-duty suspension package, and the Spicer "Twin-Grip" limited slip differential with 3.54:1 or 3.90:1 gears.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] I think it's some great little car!" *Car Craft* magazine testers bolted on better tires, headers, and traction bars to run the 1/4 mile in 13.78 seconds at 101.92 mph (164 km/h).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The muscle car market segment reached the height of popularity in 1970, but the combination of rising fuel and insurance prices along with emerging emissions reductions meant the end of an era.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors originally planned to build as many as 10,000 of the cars, but high insurance premiums killed the SC/360 after a single year's production of just 784 examples.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A total of 304 were built with the now-preferred combination of a four-speed manual transmission and a four-barrel carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Sportabout version was the most popular model by far, outselling all other Hornet models combined in its debut year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] For most of its production, it was the only American-made station wagon in its size class.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors established a new focus on quality with the 1972 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The "Buyer Protection Plan", was the industry's innovative 12-month or 12,000-mile (19,312 km) comprehensive, bumper-to-bumper warranty.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This was an industry-first that included providing a loaner car as well as trip-interruption protection, all at a time when most automakers offered only a limited six-month warranty on their new cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 1972 **AMC Buyer Protection Plan** was possible due to numerous mechanical upgrades to increase durability, as well as a focus on quality in sourcing and production.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors promoted the 1972 Hornet as "a Tough Little Car".
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The automaker promised to repair anything wrong with the car (except for the tires), and owners were provided with a toll-free telephone number to the company as well as a free loaner car if a warranty repair took overnight.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] To consolidate AMC's product offering, reduce production costs, and offer more value to consumers, the base models were dropped and all 1972 Hornets were designated as "SST" trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The single SST version of the 2-door and 4-door sedans, as well as the Sportabout station wagon, offered more items standard than the previous year's base model at about the same price.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Electric windshield wipers and washers replaced the standard vacuum-operated units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] With no stripped-down basic models, all Hornets now came with comfort and convenience items that most consumers expected.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] For the first time, an AM/FM monaural radio was added to the options list.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Other changes included dropping the SC/360 compact muscle car, but the two-barrel version of the 360 cu in (5.9 L) remained optional in addition to the 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] For those desiring more performance, a four-barrel carburetor was a dealer-installed option on the 360 V8.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Automatic transmissions were now the TorqueFlites sourced from Chrysler, and AMC called it the "Torque-Command".
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] New for the 1972 model year was the "X" package that attempted to replicate the success AMC had had with this trim option on the 1971 Gremlin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet X trim package was available on the two-door sedan and the new Sportabout.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It could be ordered with any of the available I6 and V8 engines and included rally stripes, "X" emblems, a three-spoke sports steering wheel, and 14 x 6-inch slot-style steel road wheels with C78 x 14 Polyglas blackwall tires.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A performance-oriented "Rallye" package was also introduced.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It included among other items: special lower body stripes, a full-synchromesh three-speed manual gearbox with floor shift, bucket seats, handling package, front disc brakes, 20.1 quick-ratio manual steering box, and a sports steering wheel.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It was possible to order both the Rallye and the X-package.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 1972 model year Hornet was one of the first American cars to offer a special luxury trim package created by a renowned fashion designer.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Developed in conjunction with Italian fashion designer Dr.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Aldo Gucci, the Gucci package was offered only on the Sportabout, the four-door wagon with a single sloping hatch replacing the then-traditional window/tailgate door.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Gucci option included special beige-colored upholstery fabrics on thickly padded seats and inside door panels (with red and green striping) along with Gucci logo emblems and a choice of four exterior colors: Snow White; Hunter Green; Grasshopper Green, and Yuca Tan.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Gucci model proved to be a success, with 2,583 produced in 1972 (and 2,252 more for 1973) Sportabouts that were so equipped.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors also produced a one-off Sportabout for Gucci's personal use.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The car included the 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine with three-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The interior featured leather on the door panels, cargo area as well as special front and rear center armrests.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The doors and custom-designed bucket seats received red and green striped inserts.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The instrument panel was given a centrally located, pull-out writing desk, graced with a scribbler and a sterling silver bamboo pen.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A map light at the end of a flexible arm extended from the right side of the desk while the left side carried a vanity mirror that was also mounted on a flexible stem.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The backs of the front seats included compartments as on airlines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The one on the right side opened as a snack table or provided a flat surface for playing games.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The compartment behind the driver concealed a miniature liquor cabinet, complete with four sterling silver tumbles and two decanters—all decorated with red and green enamel stripes.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors followed this designer influence in successive years with the Cardin Javelin in 1973 and the Cassini Matador in 1974, but there were no new signature designer versions after those.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This trim package concept inspired other automakers – including Ford's luxury marque, Lincoln in 1976 – to offer packages styled by other famous fashion designers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In addition to being painted green, the model included a "Baja" grain vinyl-covered roof and came standard with sport-styled wheel covers, and whitewall tires.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 engine was standard along with a three-speed Torque-Command automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Options included bucket seats, body side stripes, and the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 or 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Production was limited to 300 of this special model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The biggest visible changes among all AMC automobiles for the 1973 model year were to the Hornet line and its new model, a two-door hatchback.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] *Car and Driver* magazine called it "the styling coup of 1973".
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Other changes included a new front-end design and bodywork with a V-shaped grille, a slightly recessed and longer hood, and longer peaked front fenders.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The facelift incorporated a new stronger and larger energy-absorbing recoverable front bumper system with a horizontal rubber strip that met the new no-damage at 5-mile-per-hour (8.0 km/h) National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) safety legislation.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The rear also received a new 2.5 mph (4.0 km/h) bumper with twin vertical rubber guards, but the 5 mph unit (matching the front) was optional.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The overall length of the Hornet was increased by 6 inches (152 mm).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] For the 1973 model year, the SST designation was dropped from the Hornet line, and all were simply called Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The newly introduced two-door hatchback incorporated a fold-down rear seat for increased cargo volume from 9.5 to 30.5 cubic feet (269 to 864 L).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] An optional hinged floor made a hidden storage space that housed a temporary use "space-saver" spare tire and created a flat load area space totaling 23 cu ft (651 L).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The new hatchback was available with Levi's bucket seat interior trim option that was made of spun nylon fabric, rather than real cotton denim, to comply with flammability standards as well as offer greater wear and stain resistance.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The interior included copper Levi's rivets, traditional contrasting stitching, and a traditional Levi's tab on both the front seat backs, as well as door panels with Levis trim with removable map pockets while the exterior included "Levi's" decals on the front fenders.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] An optional dealer accessory was available to convert the open hatchback area into a recreational vehicle or camper with mosquito net windows.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Mini-Camper Kit converted an open hatchback into a camping compartment and enough room for sleeping with the rear seat folded down.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The "Mini-Camper" was a weatherproof covering that fitted over the roof section from the B-pillar back to the rear bumper that was easy to set up.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The two- and four-door sedan models were carried over while the Sportabout wagon received a new optional upscale "D/L" package.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This trim package included exterior woodgrain bodyside decal panels, a roof rack with a rear air deflector, and individual reclining seats upholstered in plush cloth.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Gucci edition wagon was continued for one more year with five exterior color choices.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The "X" package was now available only for the Sportabout and hatchback.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It included color-coordinated "rally" side stripes, 14 x 6-inch slot-style steel wheels with C78 x 14 Goodyear Polyglas tires, an "X" emblem, and a sports steering wheel.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Engines incorporated new emissions controls and the choices on all Hornet models included two I6s, the standard 232 cu in (3.8 L) or a 258 cu in (4.2 L) version, as well as two V8s, the base 304 cu in (5.0 L) or the 175 hp (130 kW; 177 PS) 360 cu in (5.9 L).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Any Hornet model could be ordered with the two-barrel 360 engine and automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Demand for classic muscle car cars had disappeared by 1973, but the Hornet was a relatively light car and was a "mildly spirited performer" in stock form with the new emissions gear.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A Hornet hatchback with the 360 V8 was tested by *Car and Driver*.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A comparison road test by *Popular Science* selected the most "trend-setting" and "deluxe compacts" with V8 engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet hatchback model was described as "one of the most modern cars on the market" and the 304 cu in (5.0 L) and automatic transmission-equipped Hornet hatchback recorded 0-60 acceleration 12.1 seconds and 16.453 mpg‑US (14.296 L/100 km; 19.759 mpg‑imp) fuel economy.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Another *Popular Science* road test of compact four-door sedans compared the AMC Hornet 304 cu in (5.0 L), Ford Maverick 302 cu in (4.9 L), Chevrolet Nova 350 cu in (5.7 L), and Plymouth Valiant 318 cu in (5.2 L).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was described as having an interior 'filled with features to make riding and driving more enjoyable" as well as good braking, handling, and maneuverability.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Spurred by AMC's success in its strategy of improving product quality, and an advertising campaign focusing on "we back them better because we build them better", the automaker achieved record profits.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors' comprehensive "Buyer Protection Plan" warranty was expanded for the 1973 models to cover lodging expenses should a car require overnight repairs when the owner is away from home.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Suggested prices began at $2,298 for the base model two-door sedan with the more popular new hatchback going for $2,449.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] All four versions of the Hornet were mostly carryovers in 1974, with minimal trim changes.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The front bumper lost its full-width vinyl rub strip but gained two rubber-faced bumper guards.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A larger energy-absorbing rear bumper was added to meet new 5 miles per hour (8.0 km/h) front and rear safety standards requiring the license plate to be moved up to a position between the taillights.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The design of these bumpers has been evaluated as not detracting from the Hornet's styling compared to some used by the competition.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] New inertial-reel seat/shoulder belts were standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Additionally, the NHTSA required all new cars to include an inexpensive technology called a "seat belt interlock mechanism" for front-seat passengers to buckle up before the engine would start.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] However, Congress quickly passed a law killing the interlock mechanism and ordering that the warning sound indicating an unsecured front seat passenger could last no more than eight seconds.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Marketing of the 1974 Hornet included placement as a lead vehicle in a James Bond movie *The Man With The Golden Gun* which included a chase scene with a red hatchback jumping a broken bridge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] All Hornet body styles saw sales gains compared to the previous year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Focusing on developing and introducing the entirely new Pacer model, AMC kept the Hornet mostly the same.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A new grille with vertical grating was the primary change.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A new "Touring Package" included special upholstery and luxury features.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In a return to its philosophy of economical compact cars, AMC emphasized its comprehensive "Buyer Protection Plan" warranty in marketing the Hornets.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Six-cylinder Hornets could be ordered with a new British-supplied Laycock de Normanville "J-type" overdrive.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Optional on cars with a manual three-speed transmission, the unit was controlled by a pushbutton at the end of the turn signal stalk.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The overdrive unit engages automatically at speeds above 35 mph (56 km/h) and drops out at 32 mph (51 km/h).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It also included an accelerator pedal kick-down switch for faster passing.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] All U.S. market Hornets featured catalytic converters and now required gasoline without tetraethyl lead.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] "Unleaded Fuel Only" warnings were displayed on both the fuel gauge and on a decal by the fuel filler.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Consumers complained loudly about the 1974 "mandatory seat belt" system, and it was replaced in 1975 with a simple reminder buzzer and light.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The U.S. economy was experiencing a period of high inflation, with American Motors increasing the suggested sticker prices by an average of 13%, and new car sales fell for all automakers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The industry sold 8.2 million units, a drop of more than 2.5 million from the record pace in 1973.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Sales of the Hornet also declined although marketing included cash rebates to buyers that ranged from $200 to $600 a car or a combination of cash and an extension of its Buyer Protection” warranty valued at $99.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] American Motors experienced success with the innovative Pacer and increased production of the unchanged 1976 model Pacers to 800 units a day.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The problem with the sales of the Pacer was the negative impact on the sales of both the compact Hornet and subcompact Gremlin models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In its sixth year as a carryover model, AMC priced the Hornet sedan and hatchback at the same as the year before with only the Sportabout slightly higher.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The 1976 model year saw the introduction of the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare twins that included a station wagon body style.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] These had a more upright top-hinged rear tailgate with a lower lift-over with greater cargo capacity than the Sportabout and they ended AMC's monopoly on domestic compact-sized wagons.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet line was mostly unchanged for 1977 with improvements made to engines and transmissions for increased fuel efficiency and the effects of new nitrogen oxides (NOx) emission standards.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] All three-speed manual transmissions shifters were now mounted on the floor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A new sports-oriented model, the AMX, was introduced to appeal to young, performance-oriented car buyers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] This model marked the return of a famous name that evoked AMC's original AMX two-seat sports car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It was one of the revived muscle cars by the domestic automakers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The AMX was available only as a hatchback with the I6 featuring a floor-shifted four-speed manual or optional floor shifted automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The only transmission with the 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was the automatic.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Standard was an upgraded black or tan interior with a floor console, "rally" instrumentation with tachometer, and a "soft-feel" sports steering wheel.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet AMX "looked the part of a true performance car" with its standard spoilers, airfoils, and body-colored rear window louvers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It was available in only four exterior colors.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Alpine White, Firecracker Red, Sunshine Yellow, or Lime Green colors included matching painted bumpers with a wraparound rubber guard strip, bodyside rubber guard strip, and contrasting AMX model identification bodyside decals ahead of the rear wheels.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Options included bright aluminum road wheels as well as large Hornet-graphic decals on the hood and a smaller one on the decklid.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] In addition to the standard upholstery colors, the Levi's interior was optional, but only 100 Hornet AMX models were so equipped.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A regional "California Edition" was available with "C.E." decals on the front fenders and an optional Audiovox stereo system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] A total of 5,207 Hornet AMX were produced for the one model year, of which 3,196 had the six-cylinder and 2,011 with the V8 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was phased out after the 1977 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] However, its robust and versatile rear-wheel-drive platform continued to serve as the foundation for subsequent AMC models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] It transformed into a new "luxury compact" line of automobiles, the AMC Concord.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] The Hornet was re-engineered and restyled to become the 1978 Concord and helped establish the "luxury compact" market segment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] With its upgraded design, components, and more standard features, the new Concord was moved upscale from the economy-focused Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Changes to the AMC's "junior" platform made the new Concord more comfortable and desirable to buyers seeking an image of luxury, as well as greater value.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p01] Furthermore, demonstrating the enduring adaptability of its original design, the Hornet's chassis underpinned the innovative "crossover" all-wheel drive line of models, the AMC Eagle, which debuted in 1979 for the 1980 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The AMC Hornet was exported to international markets, as well as assembled under license from Complete knock down (CKD) kits that were shipped from AMC's U.S. or Canadian plants.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The foreign-built cars incorporated numerous components and parts that were produced by local manufacturers to gain tax or tariff preferences.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Between 1970 and 1975, a total of 1,825 Hornets were built in right-hand-drive at the Australian Motor Industries (AMI) factory at Port Melbourne in Victoria, Australia.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The initial engineering to right-hand drive and interior design was achieved firstly with South African-built Hornets and then used as the blueprint for Australian assembly.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet was sold in Australia as the "Rambler Hornet", only in the four-door sedan body style.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] They were fitted with either a 232 cu in (3.8 L) or 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 engine and with an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Australian Hornets were a model year behind the U.S. models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In other words, the 1972 Australian model was a U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] 1973 models and therefore no Hornets were assembled in Australia for 1974.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Production resumed in 1975, with AMI making the U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] While the Hornet was the least expensive compact model in the United States, the Hornet in Australia was a luxury model, with high levels of trim, carpet, tires, and accessories.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These included high-back seats, fully lined boot and covered spare wheel.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet used a PBR fully assisted dual braking system, and front disc brakes from the Javelin Trans Am.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet sold for $3,999 in 1970, with 407 cars being sold in Australia in that year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] 1974 saw 118 sales (of cars assembled in 1973.) 1975 was the Hornet's final year in Australia, with 136 sales.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Purdy Motor would go on to assemble the Rambler American, Classic, Ambassador, Rebel, and Javelin during this time.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In 1974 a new local vehicle manufacturer, Motorizada de Costa Rica, purchased the rights of Rambler distributorship from Purdy Motors.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Motorizada continued to assemble AMC and Jeep vehicles as well as other brands.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet Sportabout debuted in Costa Rica under the unusual name of the AMC Unisex, which was known in Mexico as the American 75.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Motorizada was liquidated in 1979 allegedly for not paying taxes thereby ending the AMC brand in Costa Rica.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] American Motors Corporation held a partial stake in Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM) and produced Hornet models in Mexico from 1970 through 1977.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Available body styles included the two- and four-door sedans, as well as the four-door liftback wagon.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The cars assembled in Mexico continued to be called VAM Rambler following the tradition of the VAM-built Rambler American models until 1974.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The VAM cars came with different trims and interiors than the equivalent AMC-made models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The models also combined different front clips, such as the 1977 VAM American came with the shorter U.S. and Canadian market 1977 Gremlin front-end, while its interior trim featured premium seats and upholstery.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The engines in VAM models were based on AMC designs, but modified and built by VAM.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unique to Mexico were the 252 cu in (4.1 L) and 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These were designed to cope with the high altitudes and low octane gasoline in Mexico.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The initial VAM Rambler Americans were available in a single, nameless trim level (equivalent to the U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] SST models), with only an optional performance-minded "Rally" package for the two-door sedans, carried over from 1969.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The model was not available with the 199 cu in (3.3 L) I6 or any V8 engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The muscle-oriented SC/360 and Hornet AMX were not made, and no Levis or Gucci trims were available.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Legislation at the time allowed the manufacture of three body styles, so the hatchback version was not produced in Mexico.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] All VAM sporty versions of the Hornet were based on AMC's 1971 and 1972 two-door sedan counterparts.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike the Hornet, the now fourth-generation VAM Rambler American kept the same economy focus of its predecessor models despite its long list of standard equipment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet-based 1970 VAM Rambler American was available as a two- or four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The standard 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 producing 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) featured a 244-degree camshaft, 8.5:1 compression ratio, and a single-barrel Carter RBS or YF carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Standard was a fully synchronized three-speed manual transmission with a column-mounted shifter, a heavy-duty clutch, a 3.54:1 rear differential gear ratio, regular suspension, four-wheel drum brakes, manual steering, a four-bladed rigid-engine fan, and a regular cooling system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The VAM Rambler American sedans for 1971 were carried over from 1970.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Enhancements included VAM's 266-degree camshaft for the 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 engine, replacing AMC's 244-degree camshaft.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Despite the power increase, the engine's official output remained 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) at 4,400 rpm.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New interior colors, side armrests, and door panel designs were available.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The AM radio was updated to a newer design.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The new model year also introduced the Hornet Sportabout-based Camioneta Rambler American.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The station wagon version included the same equipment as the two sedans, plus several additional features.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Camioneta Rambler American included the parcel shelf with courtesy lights as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It was the only Mexican Hornet version to offer a three-speed automatic transmission as optional equipment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Wagons with the automatic transmission included the one-barrel 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) 232 cu in (3.8 L) engine, while those with a manual transmission had the Carter WCD carburetor rated at 155 hp (116 kW; 157 PS).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1972 model year VAM models incorporated the engineering revisions and upgrades as the U.S.-market AMC-built counterparts.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The one-barrel 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 was standard on sedans and wagons with automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Station wagons with a manual transmission featured the two-barrel 155 hp (116 kW; 157 PS) version.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This was also the first year of the seatbelt warning buzzer located above the light and wiper knobs.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Camioneta Rambler American featured the Chrysler-built TorqueFlite A904 automatic transmission, replacing the previous Borg-Warner "Shift-Command" units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1973 model year VAM Hornets were redesigned.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] They incorporated the U.S.-version with a new front-end design with larger horizontal rectangular side marker lights, semi-square headlight bezels, and a V-shaped grille and hood edge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The front bumper included AMC's five-mile-per-hour design, but without the recovering shocks; in their place were regular rigid bumper mounts as in previous years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Mexico's car safety standards were less restrictive; thus, VAMs mounted the bumpers closer to the body than their AMC counterparts.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] They featured Carter RBS/YF one-barrel carburetors, VAM's 266-degree camshafts, and an 8.5:1 compression ratio.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The three-speed automatic transmission became available as an option on sedan models, and the rear differential gear ratio was changed to 3.31:1 across all units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1974 Rambler American was a carryover.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Differences included a new rear five-mile-per-hour bumper, and the rear license plate was relocated to the center of the rear panel over the gas filler.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The seat and door panel designs were revised.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The parking brake pedal received a smaller rubber pad.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The standard wheels were VAM's new 14x6-inch five-spoke design with volcano-type hubcaps.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 included an evaporative canister to reduce emissions and a slightly lower 8.3:1 compression ratio.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Mid-year, the compression ratio was further reduced to 7.6:1.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Nevertheless, the engines remained rated at 170 hp (127 kW; 172 PS).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The introduction of the Gremlin line by VAM in 1974 became the company's smallest and most affordable model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] There was a gap between the lower-end Rambler American line and the larger, top Classic (Matador) line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The differences in size and engine series between the Rambler American and the Gremlin were not enough for VAM to create the impression of a more solid, more diverse product line, since both cars were perceived as belonging to the same economy class, which would produce internal competition.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The model was shifted from the economy segment to the mid-segment when an all-new generation was introduced in 1975.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This repositioned the company's full product line and rejuvenated the compact line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet-based Rambler American had been on the market for five years, continued to sell well, and maintained a positive image.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The name was simplified from Rambler American to just American, marking the discontinuation of the Rambler brand in Mexico.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new luxury American ECD trim level was followed by a revised and improved American Rally and American base models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These differentiated the line from the Gremlin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] All versions obtained updates and upgrades.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The American base model in its first year featured all-new rectangular amber parking lights, a grille divided into six rectangular sections, and more hexagonal-lined headlight bezels.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Manual front disk brakes were standard (though a few manual-transmission units still included front drums).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 engine was rated at 170 hp (127 kW; 172 PS) and featured Prestolite electronic ignition.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This engine was carried over with a 7.6:1 compression ratio, 266-degree camshaft, and a single-barrel Carter YF or RBS carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Interiors included new door panels available in solid or two-tone colors, as well as new seat patterns.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The two-tone dashboard was replaced by a color-keyed unit with a new "American" emblem on the glove box door and a standard fuel economy gauge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Cars equipped with an automatic transmission included a heater and power steering at no extra cost.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1976 models were almost the same as their immediate predecessors; their differences were limited to a compression ratio increase for the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 from 7.6:1 to 8.0:1.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New gauges appeared in the form of a 160 km/h speedometer and revised warning lights, sun visors were redesigned to larger more rectangular units with side bending portions, a new more-ornate dome light lens, new seat, and door panel designs, while a rear defroster was added to the options.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The separate seatbelt warning buzzer between the wiper and light knobs was discontinued.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New full-rubber bumper guards became available alongside the already existing metal ones with rubber strips.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1977 models included a facelift that AMC originally intended to be exclusive to the Gremlin line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The design included a new front bumper, squared headlight bezels with rounded corners, and an egg-crate smile-shaped grille that incorporated the rectangular parking lights from the previous two years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] An "American" emblem was mounted on the right front edge of the hood.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The two-point seatbelts were upgraded to fixed three-point units on both sedan models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Station wagons included three-point retractable units as standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Carter RBS carburetor was discontinued, leaving the YF model on the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Two-door sedans with manual transmissions now featured a floor-mounted gearshift and low-back, fold-down individual seats.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In contrast, models with automatic transmissions retained a bench seat with split-folding backs and a column-mounted shifter.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Manual transmission cars incorporated a safety lock lever in their steering column ignition switch, shared with the American Rally model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The seats and door panels were slightly modified from the previous year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new "American" emblem with different typography was applied to the glove box door.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The "258" rear-quarter-panel emblems were replaced with new "4.2" versions.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Although VAM introduced a factory-installed air conditioning system for its 1977 model year cars, it was not available for the American series.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The objective was to offer it in high-trim and performance models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] However, VAM dealerships could install a universal air conditioning system for non-factory-built units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The sports-oriented Rambler American Rally package was originally introduced in 1969 for the third-generation Rambler American two-door sedan as a more economical, sporty alternative to the muscular VAM Javelin and the personal-luxury VAM Rambler Classic SST (Rebel SST hardtop).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] With the arrival of the new Hornet-based models for 1970, the package was continued and improved, featuring not only more standard production accessories but also all-new exclusive ones.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Rambler American Rally model was available a full year before AMC's Hornet SC/360 and two years before the Hornet X and Hornet Rallye-X models, making it the first-ever performance product based on the Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The package started with an exclusive engine designed by VAM, the high-performance 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 rated at 160 hp (119 kW; 162 PS) featuring a 9.8:1 a compression ratio, a Carter WCD carburetor, and a 266-degree camshaft.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This package included a black two-spoke sports steering wheel with a central bullseye emblem, wide reclining individual front seats, and a floor-mounted Hurst Performance shifter for the 150-T three-speed manual transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A locking mechanism for the shifter connected to the steering wheel ignition switch.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Other features included a bright molding package, a rear panel overlay between the taillights, and two courtesy lights.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike the 1969 version, power drum brakes were no longer standard; they were optional.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Rambler American Rally for 1971 was almost equal to the previous year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The new script "Rally" emblems replaced the "American" fender emblems to differentiate the 1971 models from the 1970 models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new AM monaural radio model replaced the previous unit used since 1966 in Rambler American and Classic models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The success of the Rally package led VAM to use it as a trim level for 1972, along with improvements.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The safety mechanism connecting the shifter to the ignition switch was discontinued and replaced with a small safety lever on the side of the column to prevent the ignition switch from accidentally turning to the lock position while the vehicle is still in motion.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The previously optional 8000 RPM tachometer became standard equipment along with AMC's new three-arm three-spoke sports steering wheel with a round center horn button.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Low-back, smaller, more bucket-like front reclining seats replaced the wide units of the previous two years, creating a free space between the units over the transmission tunnel.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The round floor-shift base shared with 1968–1969 Javelins was replaced by a new square design.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The bright rear panel received an aluminum-look finish, and the taillight lenses featured a new, larger backup light and side stripes.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The grille was changed from aluminum to plastic, and an updated hood latch appeared.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1972 Rally engine was the VAM 252 cu in (4.1 L) I6 producing 170 hp (127 kW; 172 PS) at 4,600 rpm, 9.5:1 compression ratio and the 266-degree camshaft, which was originally used in 1969 and 1970 VAM Javelins, as well as 1970 and 1971 Rambler Classics (Rebel and Matador).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike the exclusive high-performance version of the 1970-1971 232 Rally engine, the 252 six was a regular production unit.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The only exception to this was the exclusive high-flow version of the Carter RBS single-barrel carburetor, named Carter RBS-PV1, developed by VAM's engineers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The "232 SIX" emblems were replaced with "252" design.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] For 1973, VAM sought to standardize and consolidate as many parts and components to cut costs.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Both the 232 and 252 engine series were discontinued in favor of the higher-output 170 hp (127 kW; 172 PS) 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 as the standard models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The engine now shared the same crankshaft as VAM's new 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 was introduced in the 1971 VAM Javelin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The larger-displacement engine featured unique head and exhaust porting designs with larger intake and exhaust valves, along with dished pistons with a 3.909 in (99.3 mm) bore and 3.894 in (98.9 mm) stroke.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The increase in displacement was achieved by a 0.06 in (1.5 mm) larger bore than the 258 I6.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The rear differential gear ratio changed from 3.54:1 to 3.31:1.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] High-back bucket seats were available, shared with the second-generation VAM Javelin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike previous seat backs, these did not include a reclining mechanism.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New side panel designs were accompanied by a now standard parcel shelf incorporating both courtesy lights.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The front end was updated as in the standard Rambler American models, except for the blackout grille.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The engine displacement emblems changed the last digit to eight while keeping the same design as last year's units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The rectangular "Rambler" rear emblem was removed and its place was taken by the manuscript "Rally" unit that was no longer on the front fenders.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1974 Rallys were mostly unchanged from the 1973s.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Just like on the Rambler American, their largest difference was the new rear five-mile-per-hour bumper and relocated rear license plate.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These models incorporated the first design of VAM's original five-spoke wheels, which carried full volcano-shaped hubcaps and trim rings.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Wheel covers were not available for this model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] For the first time, a set of factory-side stripes adorned the model's exterior, including a manuscript "Rally" emblem on the rear quarter panel, creating a two-tone appearance.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The front seats were the same as the year before and were now also shared with the brand-new Classic AMX (Matador X) model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The discontinuation of the original VAM logo in 1973 in favor of the new arrow-type logo meant its removal from the tachometer dial.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The shifter was changed into a T-shaped Hurst unit.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new AMC logo on a black background replaced the American Motors script on the transparent acrylic cap of the steering wheel's horn button.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The compression ratio of the 258 cu in (4.2 L) engines was reduced from 8.5:1 to 8.3:1.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The new marketing approach for VAM's compact model was also included, changing the name from Rambler American Rally to American Rally.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] For the first time, VAM sought to reposition the model higher, moving it away from the economical, sporty model status it pioneered, and incorporating luxury features.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1975 American Rally, with its new name, received its first redesign of identity emblems, featuring an all-new "RALLY" nameplate in printed letters connected by a background line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Like the former one, it was located on the rear panel between the right taillight and the rear license plate.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new grille, headlight bezels, and parking lights shared with the American and Gremlin lines were now in blackout form.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New side decals were discreet lines running the full length of the car, without altering proportions, and incorporated Rally emblems on the front fenders.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The interior, for the first time, differed from that of the American model, except for the front seats.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Rally emblems appeared etched on the front high corners of the side panels.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] All previously exposed metal parts, such as the door tops, rear sides, and B-pillar, were now upholstered in vinyl.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The "RAMBLER" emblem on the glove box was replaced by a "RALLY" one of the same design.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike all of its predecessors, a considerable number of 1975 American Rally units were equipped with the heater as standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The aspect that made the American Rally the most different from the last generation was the engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 came with an all-new Prestolite electronic ignition system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Manual front disk brakes replaced the previous drums.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new TREMEC 170-F four-speed manual transmission with Hurst linkage was available from the factory.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] However, VAM was unable to standardize it fully, and several Hurst-linked three-speed 1975 American Rally versions were built.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Since 1973, the growing problem of air pollution (especially in Mexico City) forced the Mexican government to begin emission certification of all engines produced in the country starting in 1974.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This would affect all high-compression engines of all marques.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] For this reason, the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 had dropped from an 8.5:1 to 8.3:1 compression compression between 1973 and 1974.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] However, this change was not enough to comply with government standards, and VAM was forced to further reduce compression in mid-1974.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This meant a 7.6:1 compression ratio for the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 for the second half of the year production of the 1974 Rambler American Rally.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Improvements in the form of the four-speed transmission and electronic ignition were insufficient.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In 1976, VAM introduced the Gremlin X in Mexico, retaking the economical sporty concept originally held by the Rally model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Engineers improved the output of the 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 without increasing gas emissions by adopting a higher 8.0:1 compression ratio.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This, along with the subcompact's lighter body, made the 1976 Gremlin X outperform the low-compression 1975 American Rally even though it was not offered with the new four-speed transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] To avoid internal competition between the performance models and further push the line's concept change, VAM upgraded the American Rally to differentiate it from the new subcompact model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1976 models switched to the 200 hp (149 kW; 203 PS) 7.7:1 compression ratio VAM 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 with Holley 2300 two-barrel carburetor and 266-degree camshaft, shared with the VAM Pacer and all Classic models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This marked for the first time the presence of VAM's largest engine in the Hornet-based compact line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Changes to the 258 six were still in process for the 282 as well, so the existing version was continued.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1976 American Rally had improved performance with its higher displacement, large-diameter valves, larger intake manifold, and larger carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Additionally, the 1976 American Rally included improvements such as power front disc brakes, power steering, and a tinted windshield as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The four-speed transmission and heater were also standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New seat patterns and door panel designs (without the etched Rally emblem) were used, while gauges were changed to a 160 km/h speedometer and a 6,000 RPM tachometer.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New dome light lens design and longer sun visors were shared with the American and Gremlin.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The new engine and standard equipment, coupled with the mid-year discontinuation of the 1976 Classic AMX (Matador X), made the American Rally the company's top-of-the-line performance model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The sportiness and concept were fairly close to those of the 1972–1976 VAM Javelins and Classic AMXs.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] With the engine change, the rear quarter panel emblems morphed into "4.6" units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] After only one year, the model name "Rally" emblem on the rear panel was redesigned again.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1977 models incorporated engineering upgrades for the 258 six the year before the 282 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] All-new head design with quench-type combustion chambers raised the compression ratio from 7.7:1 to 8.0:1.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It was accompanied by a new aluminum intake manifold with improved flow, while retaining the Holley 2300 two-barrel carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These improvements made the 1977 American Rally the best-performing model of its series, even surpassing the high-compression 1972 model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Despite this, advertised horsepower and torque ratings were the same as the year before.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The power increase enabled the use of a new 3.07:1 rear differential gear ratio for better fuel economy and top speed, without sacrificing acceleration or towing capacity.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The front high-back bucket seats received new patterns, and for the first time since the 1972 reclining mechanism (as standard equipment), three-point front seatbelts with double retractable mechanisms were added.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new VAM-designed digital tachometer replaced the conventional analog unit in the midyear.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The exterior featured the new Gremlin front clip.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New decals covering only the topsides of the front fenders started near the doors, at the side marker lights.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Between the lights and the stripe was a "Rally 4.6" sticker.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Like the three luxury versions of the line for the year, the 1977 American Rally was the first unit of its series to offer the original factory air conditioning system as an option.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The hood and trunk lights, as well as the glove box unit, were added to the standard equipment list.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The American Rally was discontinued in 1977 along with all other Hornet-based VAM Americans.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It would be succeeded by the 1978 American Rally AMX model (VAM's version of the 1978 AMC Concord AMX), marking the first time AMC produced its hatchback coupe body style in Mexico.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unlike the AMC Hornet X models, neither the Hornet-based Rambler American Rally nor the American Rally was ever available with V8 engines, automatic transmissions, or column-mounted shifters.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Rally model was more than just an appearance package, but it was also not as strong as a muscle car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Its closest American equivalent is the 1972 Hornet Rallye-X model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It is regarded as one of VAM's most collectible models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] As part of the shift in market strategy for VAM's Hornet-based compacts for 1975 that included advancements in the American base model and American Rally, the introduction of the new American ECD or "Edición Cantos Dorados" (English: Golden Edges Edition).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It represented for the first time that a VAM four-door compact was not an economy base model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The American ECD was VAM's first regular-production luxury compact, following the two-door hardtops of 1963 and 1965, which were marketed as the Rambler American Hardtop (equivalent to the Rambler American 440H in the U.S. and Canada).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The ECD was restricted to the four-door sedan, while the 1975 American Rally was the high-trim two-door sedan.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The station wagon remained a single-edition model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The American ECD was equivalent in the U.S. to the 1975 four-door Hornet DL model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1975 American ECD came standard with a 170 hp (127 kW; 172 PS) 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 engine with a single-barrel Carter carburetor, an electronic ignition, a 266-degree camshaft, and a 7.6:1 compression ratio with a regular cooling system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Included were manual front disk brakes with rear drums, power steering, heavy-duty suspension with front sway bar, Chrysler TorqueFlite A904 three-speed automatic transmission, and a 3.31:1 rear gear ratio.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Optional equipment included passenger's side mirror, remote-controlled driver's side mirror, power brakes, bumper guards, tinted windshield, light group, and others.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1976 American ECD included the same upgrades as the rest of the American line.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] These were longer sun visors, a 160 km/h speedometer, a new dome light lens, and a higher 8.0:1 compression ratio on the 258 six.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A rear defroster was added to the options list while the tinted windshield became standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The luxury seat patterns and wheel covers were redesigned.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] An electric analog clock appeared to the right of the speedometer, although several models kept the vacuum gauge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A new model for the year was the two-door American ECD.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This model was a limited-edition luxury American two-door sedan comparable to the 1960s Rambler American hardtops.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The equipment was the same as the four-door American ECD, with some differences.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The engine on this model was the 200 hp (149 kW; 203 PS) 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 featuring a Holley 2300 two-barrel carburetor, 7.7:1 compression ratio, 266-degree camshaft, and electronic ignition.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The automatic transmission was a floor-mounted shift design, a first in a VAM Hornet-based American.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The front seats were upgraded to high-back individual non-reclining units, replacing the four-door bench.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The American ECD was once again restricted to the four-door sedan only for 1977.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The model incorporated the new Gremlin front clip, as did the rest of the American line for the year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New "4.2" units replaced the "258" engine displacement emblems, and the bumper guards were included at no charge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Most of the light group was also installed as standard, which added illumination for the engine, trunk, and glove box.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The electric clock was fully standardized in all units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Front seat belts were upgraded to three-point retractable units.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The rear seatback received a concealed fold-down armrest.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] AMC's factory air conditioning system was added to the options.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Carter RBS one-barrel carburetor was discontinued, leaving only the Carter YF model.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A group of employees planned to take advantage of the upcoming new model to pay homage to VAM's general manager, Gabriel Fernández Sáyago, one of the most respected in the Mexican auto industry at the time, and VAM's leader since 1946.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The new personal luxury compact was named after him, using his initials as a designation.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The model was presented to him as a surprise in late 1976, which he appreciated greatly, but, opting for a more humble stance, he requested that the model not bear his name.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The employees respected his decision but managed to keep their original plan in place indirectly.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The general manager's initials were retained, but the meaning was changed to "Grand Formula Sport." The model was introduced alongside VAM's 1977 lineup as a two-door alternative to the American ECD and a luxury alternative to the American Rally.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1977 American GFS incorporated the same appearance and equipment novelties as the American ECD of the same year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Like the two-door 1976 American ECD, the model retained the individual front seat and floor-mounted automatic transmission configuration, with the notable difference of standard reclining mechanisms.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 incorporated new head and intake manifold designs as well as the 3.07:1 rear gear ratio from the American Rally model of that year.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Unique to the 1977 American GFS was its design of rear side windows and roof.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] VAM designers created a half-landau-type vinyl-covered roof that included the over the roof targa band that AMC used for its 1977 Hornet AMX models and partially covered the flip-open rear side windows, creating a thicker B-pillar.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] American Motors adopted this design for its 1978 and 1979 Concord DL/Limited two-door models, but without the targa trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] New for 1977 was VAM's first station wagon that was not an economy-based model, the first in 17 years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This was included with the optional automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Like the American GFS, the engine changed from the 282 cu in (4.6 L) to the 282 cu in (4.6 L) I6 version with a 3.07:1 rear differential gear ratio.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Like the American ECD, it shared the column-mounted gearshift, high-trimmed-upholstered bench seats (with a fold-down rear unit), and special door panels.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This introduced a luxury wagon to VAM's lineup for the first time.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] However, the low-priced base wagon was no longer available with an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] VAM wagons with this package did not have a name because it was not a trim level, but VAM and printed materials described it as the "Camioneta Automática" (automatic wagon).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Starting in 1979, and based on the U.S. market Concord station wagon, it was now named "American DL".
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] South Africa was the first international market that AMC entered the right-hand drive production of the Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Before the Hornet, the Rambler American was assembled in South Africa first by National Motor Assemblers Limited (NMA) in Durban and in 1968 at the Datsun assembly facility, Rosslyn Motor Assemblers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In 1969 Rambler production was moved to the former Chrysler plant, Motor Assemblies Limited (MA) in Durban, which had come under the control of Toyota South Africa Motors in 1964.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Motor Assemblies Limited built the American for its final year and in 1970 was its replacement the AMC Hornet four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The initial design and engineering work to right-hand drive conversion for South Africa became the blueprints used right-hand drive Hornets that were assembled in Australia.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Rambler Hornet was advertised as being "built and marketed in South Africa by Toyota South Africa Ltd, wholly owned and controlled by South Africans ... sold and serviced country-wide by 220 Toyota dealers." The Hornet was marketed through 1971.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] American Motors South Africa (Proprietary) Limited was the official license holder for the production of the Rambler Hornet at the Motor Assemblies plant.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] However, latter production was hampered by problems arising from regulations.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The nation's tariff structure considered only the weight of parts or materials made in South Africa would be calculated toward local content requirements.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The objective was to increase indigenous production.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] As a result, the last of the South African-built Rambler Hornets came equipped with 4.1 L (250 cu in) Chevrolet straight-6 engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The objective was to standardize the manufacture of vehicle components within South Africa.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Because of this, the Hornet's original AMC engine was eliminated from the marketplace, while the switch also provided greater local production volume for the General Motors engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A total of 840 Hornets were built at the Motor Assemblies plant.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] AMC Hornets were campaigned in various motorsports events.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Some technical and financial support was provided by the automaker in the early years.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Bobby Allison was AMC's factory-backed NASCAR driver, racing #12 AMC Matadors fielded by Roger Penske.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Allison also participated in short-track racing, often using a modified stock car that he re-bodied using the Hornet's sheet metal, painted in the AMC's red/white/blue racing livery and numbered 12.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Hornets were campaigned on dragstrips from 1972 and became well known by their bold red, white, and blue graphics.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Dave Street was an early Hornet racer in Northeast Pro Stock events.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Drivers on the Pro Stock circuit included Wally Booth (backed by AMC until 1974), as well as Rich Maskin and Dave Kanners captured top awards.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Booth drove a Hornet to the top qualifying spot at the 1975 NHRA U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Some drivers converted from AMC Gremlins when tests with identical engines in 1973 showed that the hatchback Hornet had an advantage with higher speeds and lower times.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The 1974 Gatornationals, as well as the 1976 NHRA U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Nationals and the World Finals were won by Wally Booth driving an AMC Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornets would do the quarter-mile in 8 seconds reaching 150 mph (241 km/h).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The last AMC Pro Stocker was campaigned through the 1982 season in American Hot Rod Association events.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] It was a Hornet AMX with nitrous injection.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In 1970, Lou Haratz drove an AMC Hornet over 14,000 miles (22,531 km) to set a new Trans-Americas record by going from Ushuaia, Argentina to Fairbanks, Alaska in 30 days and 45 minutes.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] He also went on to be the first to drive completely around the widest practical perimeter of the North, Central, and South American continents for a distance of 38,472 miles (61,915 km) in 143 days.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet received a tune-up service in Caracas as well as in Lima, and the endurance record was promoted in various popular magazine advertisements for Champion spark plugs that were standard equipment in AMC engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] From 1971 the AMC Hornet was campaigned in the International Motor Sports Association (IMSA) races.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Hornets ran in GTO class (Grand Touring type with engines of 2.5 L or more) and American Challenge (AC) class.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] American Motors provided only limited support in the form of technical help.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The cars were gutted and powered by highly modified AMC 232 straight-six engines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] In 1973, AMC cars very nearly placed 1-2-3, in a BF Goodrich Radial Challenge Series race, but Bob Hennig driving an AMC Hornet went out while in third place with only six laps to go.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] BMW driver Nick Craw and AMC Hornet driver Amos Johnson ended the IMSA series as co-champions in Class B.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Amos Johnson drove car #7, an AC Class Hornet, in the 100-mile Road Atlanta race on 17 April 1977, as well as with co-driver Dennis Shaw to finish 11th in the Hallett Motor Racing Circuit on 24 July 1977.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] A 1977 Hornet AMX was prepared by "Team Highball" from North Carolina and driven by Amos Johnson and Dennis Shaw.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Car #77 finished in 34th place in the GTO class out of the 68 that started the race by completing 475 laps, 1,824 miles (2,935 km) in the 17th Annual 24 Hours of Daytona Camel GT Challenge.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The AMC cars "were killers at places like Daytona.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Buzz Dyer drove a 1977 AMC Hornet AMX (car #77) with a V8 engine in the Sports Car Club of America (SCCA) Trans Am events at the Laguna Seca Raceway on 8 October 1978 and finished 46 laps.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Two *Hot Rod* staffers, John Fuchs and Clyde Baker, entered a 1972 AMC Hornet in the Cannonball Baker Sea-to-Shining-Sea Memorial Trophy Dash.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] This was an unofficial automobile race from New York City and Darien, CT, on the U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] Atlantic coast, to Redondo Beach, a Los Angeles suburb on the Pacific coast during the time of the newly imposed 55 mph (89 km/h) speed limit set by the National Maximum Speed Law.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] The Hornet X hatchback was modified with a 401 cu in (6.6 L) AMC V8 and auxiliary racing fuel cells to increase gasoline capacity.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p02] They finished in 13th place after driving for 41 hours and 15 minutes at an average speed of 70.4 mph (113 km/h).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] As part of a significant product placement movie appearance by AMC, a 1974 Hornet X Hatchback is featured in the James Bond film: *The Man with the Golden Gun*, where Roger Moore made his second appearance as the British secret agent.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The film's "most outrageous sequence" begins with Sheriff J.W.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Pepper, who, on holiday in Thailand with his wife, is admiring a new, red AMC Hornet in a Bangkok showroom.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The action begins as James Bond commandeers the Hornet from the dealership with Pepper in it for a car chase.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The Hornet performs an "airborne pirouette as it makes a hold-your-breath jump across a broken bridge".
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The stunt car is significantly modified with a redesigned chassis to place the steering wheel in the center and a lower stance, as well as larger wheel wells, compared to the stock Hornet used in all the other movie shots.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The 360-degree mid-air twisting corkscrew was captured in just one filming sequence.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Seven tests were performed in advance before the one jump performed by an uncredited British stuntman "Bumps" Williard for the film with six (or eight, depending on the source) cameras simultaneously rolling.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Two frogmen were positioned in the water, as well as an emergency vehicle and a crane were ready, but not needed.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The Cornell Aeronautical Laboratory (CAL) was used for computer modeling to calculate the stunt.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The modeling called for a 1,460.06 kg (3,219 lb) weight of both the car and driver, the exact angles of the ramps, and the 15.86-metre (52 ft) distance between the ramps, as well as the 64.36-kilometre-per-hour (40 mph) launch speed.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This stunt was adapted from Jay Milligan's Astro Spiral Javelin show cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] These were jumps performed in AMC-sponsored thrill shows at fairs around the US, including the Houston Astrodome, where Gremlins and Hornets were also used to drive around in circles on their side two wheels in the arena.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Using exactly the same ramp design, movie set designers made the ramps look convincingly like a rickety old bridge that was falling apart.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] However, the movie's director ruined the continuous spiral effect of the stunt.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] By cutting camera shots as the car was in mid-air, they made it look like trick photography to get the car upside-down rather than filming it as one continuous jump.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Months of difficult work went into the scene that lasts only fifteen seconds in the movie.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The *Guinness World Records 2010* book describes this "revolutionary jump" as the "first astro spiral used in a movie" and lists it as third among the top ten James Bond film stunts.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The actual Bond Hornet was preserved in the National Motor Museum in Beaulieu, UK together with other famous items owned by the Ian Fleming Foundation and used in the 007 films.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In 2017, the car stunt car "in operable and in as-jumped condition" was auctioned by the museum.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The AMC Hornet is one of Hagerty's favorite Bond cars for vintage automobile collectors on a budget.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Several scale models of the AMC Hornet are available including the James Bond hatchback versions made by Corgi Toys and Johnny Lightning.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The AMC Hornet served as a vehicle for several experimental alternative fuel and power sources.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In the aftermath of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1970, research grants were funded by the U.S. government to further develop automotive gas turbine technology.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This included conceptual design studies and vehicles for improved passenger-car gas-turbine systems that were conducted by Chrysler, General Motors (through its Detroit Diesel Allison Division), Ford in collaboration with AiResearch, and Williams Research teamed with American Motors.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In 1971, a long-term test was conducted to evaluate actual road experience with a turbine-powered passenger car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] An AMC Hornet was converted to a WR-26 regenerative gas turbine power made by Williams International.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] A small-sized Williams gas turbine engine powered 1973 Hornet was used by New York City to evaluate comparable cost efficiency with piston engines and funded by a grant from the National Air Pollution Control Administration, a predecessor of the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The city was interested in "solving the air quality problems that New Yorkers were beginning to notice." The Hornet's experimental power source was developed by inventor Sam B.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Weighing in at 250 lb (113 kg) and measuring 26 by 24 in (660 by 610 mm) and 16 in (406 mm) high, it produced 80 hp (60 kW; 81 PS) at 4450 rpm with a clean exhaust.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The engines performed well in theory and ran well, especially during tests on the Michigan International Speedway, but the cars needed more work to be adapted to the turbine engine for city driving and lacked the refinement of the purpose-built Chrysler Turbine Car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Research to develop a Straticharge Continuous Fuel-Injection (SCFI) system (an early gasoline direct injection (GDI) design) was conducted with the backing of AMC.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The Hornet's conventional spark-ignited internal combustion I6 engine was a modified with a redesigned cylinder head.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Road testing was performed using a 1973 AMC Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This SCFI system was a mechanical device that automatically responded to the engine's airflow and loading conditions with two separate fuel-control pressures supplied to two sets of continuous-flow injectors.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] It was "a dual-chamber, three-valve, fuel-injected, stratified-charge" engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Flexibility was designed into the SCFI system for trimming it to a particular engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In 1976, the California Air Resources Board bought and converted AMC Hornets for its design research into hybrids.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The Consumers Gas Company (now Consumers Energy) operated a fleet of 1970 AMC Hornets converted to a dual-fuel system that was capable of using gasoline as well as compressed natural gas (CNG).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This was an early demonstration project for clean and efficient vehicles.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In 1971, the Electric Fuel Propulsion Company began marketing the Electrosport, a plug-in electric vehicle (PEV) based on the Hornet Sportabout wagon.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) conducted extensive tests of 1974 and 1975 AMC Hornets to evaluate the fuel economy claims made for the LaForce Ventur-E modifications.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The LaForce prepared Hornet included a special carburetor that was designed to vary the fuel to air mixture under all operating conditions.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Other modifications were made to the camshaft, a smaller combustion area, special "dual" exhaust manifolds, and the installation of solid valve lifters (in place of the standard hydraulic tappets).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The manifold was designed to intercept gasoline between the carburetor and engine and "to use even the harder to burn heavy gasoline molecules" – thus, claiming mileage increases of 40 to 57%.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] However, the EPA tests did not fully support the performance and economy claims that were to be achieved by these modifications in comparison to standard factory tuned vehicles.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The AMC Hornet platform served as the basis for evaluating design and styling ideas by AMC.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In the late-2000s, the Hornet name was revived for a Dodge concept car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Although both predecessor companies (Nash and Hudson) had built work trucks, the merged successor (American Motors Corporation) never developed and marketed a truck line until it purchased Jeep.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In the early 1970s, AMC was planning a compact coupé utility (pickup) based on the Hornet to compete with the increasing sales of Japanese compact pickup models.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Work began by having the Jeep styling studio convert a Hornet into a pickup with three objectives: to compete in size with the imported trucks, rival the Chevrolet El Camino in appearance, and have a lower cost than both of them.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] A further goal was to achieve the most return from AMC's $40 million investment in engineering and production dies needed to bring the sleek Hornet compact to market.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Prototypes called the **Cowboy** were developed under the leadership of Jim Alexander.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Documentation from the development process indicates three prototypes with a Hornet-based cab, Jeep-style grille treatments, and a Gremlin version.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The initial design called for a 6 feet (1.8 m) cargo box and the prototype used the front doors from a four-door Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This short cab version was not effective and the cab was opened up by incorporating the longer two-door sedan doors along with a new upper window frame and a "K-pillar effect" that improved the design and for better sight lines.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] One prototype vehicle that was painted red featured a modified AMC Gremlin front design and a cargo box with a Jeep logo on the tailgate, but did not include a four-wheel-drive system.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] A prototype finished in green and white was made using a Hornet SC/360 that featured the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engine with a floor-mounted manual transmission, radio, air conditioning, and a drop-down tailgate with no manufacturer's name stamped on it.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The third prototype had a Gremlin front-end, was painted yellow, and had a 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The basic AMC engines would be more powerful than the typical four-cylinder engines featured in the imported pickups.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] American Motors was also developing a hatchback version of the Hornet.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] However, AMC's assembly plants in Kenosha and Milwaukee were already running at maximum capacity so the chosen body style would be built in Brampton, Ontario.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] With the increasing sales of the Hornet models, the 1970 acquisition of Jeep, and no 4WD option ready for the Cowboy (at the time all Jeeps were 4WD), AMC's product planners shelved the Cowboy truck program.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The only surviving prototype was built using a 1971 Hornet SC/360 with the 360 V8 and a four-speed manual transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The automaker used it on their proving grounds for several years before being sold to Alexander, who later installed a 1973 Hornet updated front-end.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In 1973, the **Hornet GT** toured auto shows as an asymmetrical styling exercise.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The left (or driver's) side featured more glass area and a narrower "C" pillar for better visibility in comparison to the concept car's different design on its right side.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] Using different designs on each side is common practice within automobile styling studios, especially when money was tight; however, showing such an example to the public was unusual and AMC was not afraid to measure consumer reaction to new ideas.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] A mini-sized front-wheel-drive, concept car called Hornet was designed and developed by Dodge in 2006 for possible production in 2008 as the brand was entering European markets and attracting younger customers.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] As the price of fuel increased, Chrysler continued work to launch the Hornet in 2010 in Europe, the United States and other markets.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] This Hornet project may have been cancelled as part of Fiat's partnership with Chrysler; but it was also rumored that the Hornet nameplate would instead be applied to a small Dodge sedan slated for introduction in 2012 based on the same "C-Evo" platform as the Alfa Romeo Giulietta.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] In October 2011, Chrysler trademarked four names: Hornet, Dart, Duster, and Camber.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] One month later, the head of the Dodge brand, Reid Bigland, stated that Hornet would not be used for the new car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The automaker "surprised industry pundits and insiders" with an announcement that the small sedan for 2013 will be called the Dodge Dart (PF).
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] For the 2023 model year, Dodge revived the Hornet nameplate by introducing a compact crossover car.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The historic name uses the same platform as the Alfa Romeo Tonale, but the Dodge version targets the performance market segment.
[src:dodge-aspen/amc-hornet-p03] The Dodge Hornet builds on the Hudson Hornet, the AMC Hornet, and the Hornet by Dodge concept car image to focus the new Hornet as part of the "Brotherhood of Muscle" marketing.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] An **anti-roll bar** (**roll bar**, **anti-sway bar**, **sway bar**, **stabilizer bar**) is an automobile suspension part that helps reduce the body roll of a vehicle during fast cornering or over road irregularities.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] It links opposite front or rear wheels to a torsion spring using short lever arms for anchors.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This increases the suspension's roll stiffness—its resistance to roll in turns.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The first stabilizer bar patent was awarded to Canadian inventor Stephen Coleman of Fredericton, New Brunswick on April 22, 1919.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Anti-roll bars were unusual on pre-WW2 cars due to the generally much stiffer suspension and acceptance of body roll.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] From the 1950s on, however, production cars were more commonly fitted with anti-roll bars, especially those vehicles with softer coil spring suspension.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] An anti-sway or anti-roll bar is intended to reduce the lateral tilt (roll) of the vehicle on curves, sharp corners, or large bumps.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Although there are many variations in design, the object is to induce a vehicle's body to remain as level as possible by forcing the opposite wheel's shock absorber, spring, or suspension rod in the same direction as the one being impacted.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] In a turn, a vehicle compresses its outer wheel's suspension.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The anti-roll bar forces the opposite (inner) wheel's suspension to compress as well, thereby keeping the body in a more level lateral attitude.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This has the additional benefit of lowering its center of gravity during a turn, increasing its stability.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] When both front and rear anti-roll bars are fitted, their combined effect can help maintain a vehicle's tendency to roll towards the general slope of the terrain.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] An anti-roll bar is usually a torsion spring anchored to resist body roll motions.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] It is usually constructed out of a cylindrical steel bar, formed into a "U" shape, that connects to the body at two points along its longer center section, and on each end.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] When the left and right wheels move together the bar simply rotates on its central mounting points.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] When the wheels move relative to each other, torsion forces cause the bar to twist.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Each end of the bar is connected to an *end link* through a flexible joint.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The link is connected in turn to a spot near a wheel or axle, transferring forces from the heavily loaded side of a suspension to the opposite.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] 5. to the opposite side of the suspension.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The bar resists the torsion through its stiffness.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The stiffness of an anti-roll bar is proportional to the stiffness of the material, the fourth power of its radius, and the inverse of the length of the lever arms (i.e., the shorter the lever arm, the stiffer the bar).
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Stiffness is also related to the geometry of the mounting points and the rigidity of the bar's mounting points.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The stiffer the bar, the more force required to move the left and right wheels relative to each other.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This increases the amount of force required to make the body roll.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] In a turn the sprung mass of the vehicle's body produces a lateral force at the centre of gravity (CG), proportional to lateral acceleration.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Because the CG is usually not on the roll axis, the lateral force creates a moment about the roll axis that tends to roll the body.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] (The roll axis is a line that joins the front and rear roll centers).
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Roll couple is resisted by the suspension roll stiffness, which is a function of the spring rate of the vehicle's springs and of the anti-roll bars, if any.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The use of anti-roll bars allows designers to reduce roll without making the suspension's springs stiffer in the vertical plane, which allows improved body control with less compromise of ride quality.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] One effect of body lean, for typical unibody suspension geometry, is positive camber of the wheels on the outside of the turn and negative on the inside, which reduces their cornering grip (especially with cross ply tires).
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Anti-roll bars provide two main functions.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This is dependent on the total roll stiffness of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Increasing this stiffness does not change the steady state total load (weight) transfer from the inside wheels to the outside, it only reduces body lean.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The total lateral load transfer is determined by the center of gravity height and track width.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The other function of anti-roll bars is to tune the handling balance of a car.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Understeer or oversteer can be reduced by changing the proportion of the total roll stiffness that comes from the front and rear axles.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Increasing it at the front increases the proportion of the total load transfer that the front axle reacts to—and decreases it in the rear.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] In general, this makes the outer front wheel run at a comparatively higher slip angle, and the outer rear wheel to run at a comparatively lower slip angle, increasing understeer.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Increasing the proportion of roll stiffness at the rear axle has the opposite effect, decreasing understeer.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Because an anti-roll bar connects wheels on opposite sides of the vehicle, the bar transmits the force of a bump on one wheel to the opposite wheel.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] On rough or broken pavement, anti-roll bars can produce jarring, side-to-side body motions (a "waddling" sensation), which increase in severity with the diameter and stiffness of the anti-roll bars.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Other suspension techniques can delay or dampen this effect of the connecting bar.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Excessive roll stiffness, typically achieved by configuring an anti-roll bar too aggressively, can make the inside wheels lift off the ground during hard cornering.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This can be used to advantage: many front wheel drive production cars lift a rear wheel when cornering hard in order to overload the opposite wheel, limiting understeer.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Some anti-roll bars, particularly those intended for use in auto racing, are externally adjustable while the car is in the pit, whereas some systems can be adjusted in real time by the driver from inside the car, such as in Super GT.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This allows the stiffness to be altered, for example by increasing or reducing the length of the lever arms on some systems, or by rotating a flat lever arm from a stiff edge-on position to a more flexible flat-side-on position on other systems.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This lets a mechanic tune the roll stiffness for different situations without replacing the entire bar.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The MacPherson strut is a common form of strut suspension.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This was not the first attempt at strut suspension, but in MacPherson's original patent, the anti-roll bar forms an integral and essential part of the suspension, in addition to its usual function in controlling body roll.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] A strut suspension like MacPherson's requires a hinged lower member between the chassis and wheel hub to control the wheel position both inwards and outwards (controlling the track), and also forwards and backwards.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] This may be provided by a wishbone with a number of joints, or by using an additional radius rod.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] MacPherson's design replaced the wishbone with a simpler and cheaper track control arm, with a single inboard joint, to control the track.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Forward and backward position was controlled through the anti-roll bar.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Overall this required a simpler and cheaper set of suspension members than with wishbones, also allowing a reduction in unsprung weight.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] As the anti-roll bar is required to control wheel position, the bars of a MacPherson strut suspension may be connected through ball joints.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] However many later "MacPherson strut" suspensions have reverted to using wishbones rather than the simplified track control arm of the original design.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Various methods of decoupling the anti-roll bar have been proposed.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The first production car to use a semi-active anti-roll bar was the 1988 Mitsubishi Mirage Cyborg.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The 16-valve turbo model's "Dual Mode Suspension" has a dashboard- operated hydraulic actuator built into the front anti-roll bar link, allowing it to toggle between sport and touring modes.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The Jeep Wrangler (JK, JL) and Jeep Gladiator (JT) also have a switchable decoupler on Rubicon models, to increase wheel articulation for off-roading.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The first active anti-roll bar system was Citroën's SC.CAR (Systeme Citroën de Contrôle Actif du Roulis), debuted in its 1994 Xantia Activa, a medium-sized European sedan.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The anti-roll bar could be stiffened by the suspension ECU during hard cornering, minimizing body roll to 2 degrees.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class Active Body Control system eliminates the anti-roll bar, instead using sensors to detect lateral load, lateral force, and height difference in the suspension strut, which then hydraulically raise or lower the spring to counter roll.
[src:dodge-aspen/anti-sway-bar] Toyota also uses a mechanical system called Kinetic Dynamic Suspension System (KDSS) that essentially disengages the stabilizer bars when off-road, allowing for greater vehicle articulation and ride quality.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Founded as a mining camp during the Colorado Silver Boom and later named Aspen for the abundance of aspen trees in the area, the city boomed during the 1880s, its first decade.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The boom ended when the Panic of 1893 led to a collapse of the silver market.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] For the next half-century, known as "the quiet years", the population steadily declined, reaching a nadir of fewer than 1000 by 1930.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen's fortunes recovered in the mid-20th century when neighboring Aspen Mountain was developed into a ski resort, and industrialist Walter Paepcke bought many properties in the city in the 1950s and redeveloped them.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Today it is home to three institutions, two of which Paepcke helped found, having international importance: the Aspen Music Festival and School, the Aspen Institute, and the Aspen Center for Physics.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In the late 20th century, the town became a popular retreat for celebrities.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Thompson worked out of a downtown hotel and ran unsuccessfully for county sheriff.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Singer John Denver wrote two songs about Aspen after settling there.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Both figures popularized Aspen among the counter-cultural youth of the 1970s as an ideal place to live, and the city continued to grow even as it gained notoriety for some of the era's hedonistic excesses (particularly its drug culture).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen remains popular as a year-round destination for locals, multiple-home buyers and tourists.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Outdoor recreation in the surrounding White River National Forest serves as a summertime counterpart to the city's four ski areas.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Prime residential real estate in Aspen is the most expensive of any ski resort in the world on a per-square-foot basis, according to a study of 44 global ski resorts.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The city's roots are traced to the winter of 1879, when a group of miners ignored pleas by Frederick Pitkin, Governor of Colorado, to return across the Continental Divide to avoid a Ute uprising.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Utes were fighting to maintain possession of their land and communities.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Originally named Ute City, the small community was renamed Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Aspen, Colorado, post office opened on June 7, 1880.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Pitkin County was created on February 23, 1881, with Aspen as its first and only seat.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Town of Aspen was incorporated on April 1, 1881.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In its peak production years of 1891 and 1892, Aspen surpassed Leadville as the United States' most productive silver-mining district.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Production expanded due to the passage of the Sherman Silver Purchase Act of 1890, which doubled the government's purchase of silver.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In 1883, the Apostolic Vicarate of Colorado's Bishop Machebeuf had the Reverend Edward Downey establish the first Catholic mission in Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] By 1893, Aspen had banks, a hospital, a police department, two theaters, an opera house, and electric lights.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Economic collapse came with the Panic of 1893, when President Cleveland called a special session of Congress and repealed the act.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Within weeks, many of the Aspen mines were closed and thousands of miners were put out of work.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] It was proposed that silver be recognized as legal tender and the People's Party (populists) adopted that as one of its main issues.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Waite, an Aspen newspaperman and agitator, was elected governor of Colorado on the Democratic ticket, but in time the movement failed.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] During the silver boom of the 1880s, two railroads raced to reach Aspen: the **Colorado Midland**, advancing westward from Leadville, and the **Denver and Rio Grande**, approaching from Glenwood Springs.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] By **mid-October 1886**, the Colorado Midland had extended its track to **Aspen Junction** (present-day **Basalt**) —located at the confluence of the Roaring Fork and Frying Pan rivers—approximately 20 miles from Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In the **same week**, the Denver and Rio Grande completed its line into Aspen, becoming the first railroad to provide direct rail service to the town.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Colorado Midland continued construction toward Aspen, with track reaching **Maroon Creek** by December 1887.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Progress was slowed by delays in the construction of a steel viaduct (Maroon Creek Bridge), caused by late delivery of steel, which postponed the arrival of Midland trains into the town.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Despite these setbacks, the Colorado Midland ultimately completed the line, and in **early February 1888**, the first Midland train arrived in Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Passenger train service into Aspen permanently ceased on February 24, 1948.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In August 1968, freight train service into Aspen ceased.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Eventually, after wage cuts, mining revived somewhat, but production declined and by the 1930 census only 705 residents remained.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Remaining, however, were stocks of old commercial buildings and residences, along with excellent snow.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen's development as a ski resort began in the 1930s when investors conceived of a ski area, but the project was interrupted by World War II.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Friedl Pfeifer, a member of the 10th Mountain Division who had trained in the area, returned to the area and linked up with industrialist Walter Paepcke and his wife Elizabeth.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Aspen Skiing Company was founded in 1946 and the city quickly became a well-known resort, hosting the FIS World Championships in 1950.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Paepcke also played an important role in bringing the Goethe Bicentennial Convocation to Aspen in 1949, an event held in a newly designed tent by the architect Eero Saarinen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen was then on the path to becoming an internationally known ski resort and cultural center, home of the Aspen Music Festival and School.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The area would continue to grow with the development of three additional ski areas, Buttermilk (1958), Aspen Highlands (1958), and Snowmass (1967).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In the 1970s, Aspen became known as a playground for the rich and famous.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Notable celebrities frequented the town and ski slopes, also John Denver was one of the more famous permanent residents.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In 1978, Aspen was thoroughly photographed for the Aspen Movie Map project funded by the U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Movie Map is one of the earliest examples of virtual reality software.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] In 1999, the city council passed a resolution to petition the US Congress and President Clinton to restrict US immigration.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen residents cited concerns about the environmental impacts of increased immigration on their community, including urban and suburban sprawl, pollution from the older automobiles typically driven by immigrants, and litter accumulating in the mountains attributable to the increasing population.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The impetus for the resolution was the increasing number of trailer parks that housed the migrant workers employed locally in the service sector and ski industry.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The parks were perceived to be degrading to the town's image, property values, and environment.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The move was led by Terry Paulson, an Aspen City Council member, and supported and guided by national groups such as the Carrying Capacity Network, and the Center for Immigration Studies.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The resolution was discussed on the *American Patrol Report* website, contributing to a controversy over whether or not the resolution was racially motivated.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Councilman Terry Paulson and some Aspen citizens insisted that it was motivated entirely by environmental concerns.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen is notable as the smallest radio market tracked by Arbitron, ranked number 302.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] At the same time, in stark contrast to its historic character, the city has emerged into international fame as a glitzy playground of the wealthy and famous.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen has become a second and third home to many international jet-setters.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Many people from the U.S. and abroad vacation in Aspen, especially during the winter.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The downtown has been largely transformed into an upscale shopping district that includes high-end restaurants, salons, and boutiques.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Stores such as Gucci, Prada and Fendi dot South Mill Street and act as a "Rodeo Drive" of Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The city sits along the southeast (upper) end of the Roaring Fork Valley, along the Roaring Fork River, a tributary of the Colorado River about 40 miles (64 km) south of Glenwood Springs, Colorado.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] It is surrounded by mountain and wilderness areas on three sides: Red Mountain to the north, Smuggler Mountain to the east, and Aspen Mountain to the south.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen is located along State Highway 82.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] At the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 2,469 acres (9.992 km2), all of it land.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Under the Köppen climate classification, Aspen has a humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] It has a large diurnal temperature variation with moderately warm summer days very cold winter nights.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Summer lows and winter highs are relatively moderate, and frosts are rare in summer and winter days often averaging above freezing.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] As of the 2020 census, Aspen had a population of 7,004.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] 14.6% of residents were under the age of 18 and 16.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] For every 100 females there were 102.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 103.6 males age 18 and over.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] 99.8% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.2% lived in rural areas.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] There were 3,540 households in Aspen, of which 19.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Of all households, 31.7% were married-couple households, 29.6% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] There were 6,197 housing units, of which 42.9% were vacant.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 13.8%.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] As of the 2000 census, there were 5,914 people, 2,903 households, and 1,082 families residing in the city.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The population density was 1,675.4 inhabitants per square mile (646.9/km2).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] There were 4,354 housing units at an average density of 1,233.5 per square mile (476.2 per km2).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The racial makeup of the city was 94.94 percent White, 0.44 percent Black or African American, 0.24 percent Native American, 1.45 percent Asian, 0.08 percent Pacific Islander, 1.64 percent from other races, and 1.2 percent from two or more races.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 6.14 percent of the population.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] There were 2,903 households, of which 16.5 percent had children under the age of 18 living with them, 28.8 percent were married couples living together, 5.6 percent had a female householder with no husband present, and 62.7 percent were non-families.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Single individuals composed 43.8 percent of all households, and 4.8 percent had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The average household size was 1.94 and the average family size was 2.67.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The ages of the population were 13.1 percent under the age of 18, 9.8 percent from 18 to 24, 42.1 percent from 25 to 44, 27.6 percent from 45 to 64, and 7.4 percent who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 115.1 males.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 117.5 males.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The median income for a household in the city was $53,750, and the median income for a family was $70,300.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Males had a median income of $41,011 versus $32,023 for females.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The per capita income for the city was $40,680.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] About 3.6 percent of families and 8.2 percent of the population were below the poverty line, including 4.4 percent of those under age 18 and 2.6 percent of those age 65 or over.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen's single-family home prices are among the highest of any town in the country.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Real estate supply is restricted due to a moratorium on new housing construction, housing renovation and short-term rentals.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The median sales price of a single family home in 2021 in Aspen was $9.5 million.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] A 2023 study by Savills, a global real estate broker, declared that prime Aspen real estate was the most expensive on a per-square-foot-basis of the 44 global ski resort markets it studied.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Relatively less expensive housing can be found outside the city limits, in nearby Snowmass Village (median single family home price $5.2 million in 2021), or in the city's condos, many of which date to the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Affordability of housing is a severe challenge for workers in the Aspen area.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Aspen Pitkin County Housing Authority oversees an extensive program of properties intended for people who primarily live and work in the Roaring Fork Valley and whose income falls below certain limits, known as Employee Housing.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Homes purchased through Employee Housing programs typically contain deed restrictions to maintain a degree of affordability for local residents, but even deed-restricted properties in the area can cost close to $1 million.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Winter X Games sports event has been held in Aspen at Buttermilk (ski area) since 2002.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen natives Torin Yater-Wallace and Alex Ferreira are both freestyle skiers who compete in the Winter X Games and have very successful careers.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Both Torin and Alex have represented the United States of America in Men's Ski SuperPipe at the Olympic Games.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Gentlemen of Aspen is the local rugby team.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The Gentlemen of Aspen won the Rugby Super League several times: 1997, 2001, and 2002.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Aspen is a home rule municipality under Colorado law.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] An elected council of four members and the mayor supervise the city's operations, managed on a day-to-day basis by the city manager, an appointed official who serves at their pleasure.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The city's main office is at City Hall, the former Armory Hall listed on the National Register of Historic Places at the intersection of South Galena Street and East Hopkins Avenue.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Because of its expansion in the late-20th century, it has outgrown that space.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Several city departments are housed in satellite offices around the city.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] As of 2012, based on data from the 2009–10 school year, according to *U.S.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] News & World Report*, Aspen High School, the only high school in the Aspen School District, is the top ranked high school in Colorado and ranked 59th in the United States.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The high school has grades 9 to 12, 540 students, and 41 teachers.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Olympic cross-country skier Noah Hoffman is a 2007 graduate.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Minorities, mostly Hispanic, make up 13 percent of the school's enrollment.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] Four percent of the students are economically disadvantaged.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-colorado] The school has a high rate of participation in the International Baccalaureate program.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Aspen Highlands was founded and the land developed in 1958 by Aspen resident Whip Jones.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] In 1993 Jones donated it to his alma mater, Harvard University.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Harvard sold the resort to Houston, Texas developer Gerald D.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] It later became part of the Aspen Skiing Company.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Aspen Highlands has become most famous for the Highland Bowl and other experts only terrain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] However, the Bowl wasn't completely opened until 2002.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Most of the mountain's terrain flows off of the narrow ridge extending from Highland Peak.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Rolling wide intermediate trails through thick lodgepole pine forest constitute most of the mid-to-lower mountain terrain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The very bottom of the mountain is dominated by the Thunderbowl, an expansive steep intermediate run that normally hosts most of the ski competitions on the mountain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The lower mountain also contains challenging expert runs such as Lower Stein, Golden Horn Woods, and The P-Chutes.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] It is served by the Exhibition and Thunderbowl lifts.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Mid-Mountain area is anchored by the 60s era Merry-Go-Round restaurant, with a large, south-facing deck.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Merry-Go-Round also serves as the hub of the major chairlifts on mountain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Cloud Nine lift serves primarily intermediate and difficult runs on the mid-mountain as well as Scarlett's, a mogul run.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The summit of Cloud Nine lift is the location of Cloud Nine Bistro, with views of the Maroon Bells.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] As of December 2017, Aspen Highlands has changed its trail map so that there is no more beginner terrain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] This is presumably to encourage novice skiers to go to Buttermilk or Snowmass.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] What attracts most skiers to Highlands is the dramatic, just-above-timberline summit of the mountain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The upper mountain is primarily served by the Loge Peak high speed quad originating at the Merry-Go-Round.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The ridge that extends down from Loge Peak (the lift-served summit) has only one intermediate run, Broadway, which follows the ridge spine.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] On the skiers' right side is Steeplechase, an area of long and steep terrain with some runs reaching upwards of 45 degrees.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Farther down is the Olympic bowl which contains steep slopes in and out of glades.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Views of the Maroon Bells, Pyramid Peak, **Hayden Mountain**, and the Highland Bowl greet skiers at the summit.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Since 2002, the Highland Bowl has been the crown jewel of Aspen Highlands.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Most of the terrain is accessed only by hiking from the top of Loge Peak, although a snowcat can cut the distance by a third.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Including the hike-to terrain in Highland Bowl, Highlands' skiable vertical descent increases to 4,342 feet (1,323 m).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Highlands ski patrol monitors the Bowl and conducts avalanche control for skier safety.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Bowl faces primarily east, towards Aspen Mountain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Generally, the best snow to be found is in the north-facing G-Zones ("G" corresponds to green ski wax, for the coldest temperature snow).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The B-Zones (for blue wax) face east and descend down the center of the bowl from the 12,392 ft (3,777 m) summit of Highland Peak.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The south-facing Y-Zones (yellow wax), are the steepest, with slopes as steep as 48 degrees, according to Aspen Highlands trail maps.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Prior to the construction of the Deep Temerity lift in 2005, a run down the Highland Bowl required then taking the Grand Traverse, a long, flat catwalk, to get back to the Loge Peak lift.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The Highland Bowl also offers access from the summit into the steep and highly avalanche prone backcountry Five Fingers Bowl.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] On March 31, 1984, ski patrolmen Chris Kessler, Tom Snyder, and Craig Soddy were completing avalanche control work in Highland Bowl.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The three set off explosive charges near the top of the Bowl.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Their bombs yielded no sign of danger and they continued to do explosive work.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Their second explosion triggered a slide and before the three could escape an avalanche fell from above them.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] A monument in their memory has been erected near the top of the Loge Peak lift above the ski runs named in their honor (Kessler's Bowl, Snyder's Ridge, and Soddbuster).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Just before the 2005–2006 season The Aspen Skiing Company completed work on the new fixed grip triple lift "Deep Temerity".
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] The $2.7 million project eliminated the lengthy trek out from the bottom of the Highland Bowl, the Temerity glades, and Steeplechase.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] 180 acres (0.73 km2) of new terrain accompany the Deep Temerity lift for the 05–06 season, with the ultimate potential for 270 acres (1.1 km2) of new terrain.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] This will push Aspen Highlands' total area over 1,000 acres (4.0 km2).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen-highlands] Aspen Highlands, was the backdrop for the bowl skiing in the 1993 movie Aspen Extreme.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspen trees are all native to cold regions with cool summers, in the north of the northern hemisphere, extending south at high-altitude areas such as mountains or high plains.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] They are all medium-sized deciduous trees reaching 15–30 m (50–100 ft) tall.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] In North America, the aspen is referred to as quaking aspen or trembling aspen because the leaves "quake" or tremble in the wind.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] This is due to their flattened petioles which reduce aerodynamic drag on the trunk and branches.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspens typically grow in environments that are otherwise dominated by coniferous tree species, and which are often lacking other large deciduous tree species.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspens have evolved several adaptations that aid their survival in such environments.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] One is the flattened leaf petiole, which reduces aerodynamic drag during high winds and decreases the likelihood of trunk or branch damage.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Dropping leaves in the winter (like most but not all other deciduous plants) also helps to prevent damage from heavy winter snow.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Additionally, the bark is photosynthetic, meaning that growth is still possible after the leaves have been dropped.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] The bark also contains lenticels that serve as pores for gas exchange, in which their respiratory function resembles that of the stomata on leaves.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspens are also aided by the rhizomatic nature of their root systems.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Most aspens grow in large clonal colonies, derived from a single seedling, and spread by means of root suckers; new stems in the colony may appear at up to 30–40 m (100–130 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Each individual tree can live for 40–150 years above ground, but the root system of the colony is long-lived.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] In some cases, this is for thousands of years, sending up new trunks as the older trunks die off above ground.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] For this reason, it is considered to be an indicator of ancient woodlands.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] One such colony in Utah, given the nickname of "Pando", has been estimated as being 80,000 years of age; if validated, this would likely make it the oldest living colony of aspens.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Some aspen colonies become very large with time, spreading about 1 m (3 ft) per year, eventually covering many hectares.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] They are able to survive forest fires, because the roots are below the heat of the fire, and new sprouts appear after the fire burns out.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] The high stem turnover rate combined with the clonal growth leads to proliferation in aspen colonies.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] The high stem turnover regime supports a diverse herbaceous understory.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspen seedlings do not thrive in the shade, and it is difficult for seedlings to establish in an already mature aspen stand.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Fire indirectly benefits aspen trees, since it allows the saplings to flourish in open sunlight in the burned landscape, devoid of other competing tree species.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspens have increased in popularity as a forestry cultivation species, mostly because of their fast growth rate and ability to regenerate from sprouts.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] This lowers the cost of reforestation after harvesting since no planting or sowing is required.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] In contrast with many trees, aspen bark is base-rich, meaning aspens are important hosts for bryophytes and act as food plants for the larvae of butterfly (Lepidoptera) species.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Young aspen bark is an important seasonal forage for the European hare and other animals in early spring.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspen is also a preferred food of the European beaver.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Elk, deer, and moose not only eat the leaves but also strip the bark with their front teeth.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspen wood is white and soft, but fairly strong, and has low flammability.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] It has a number of uses, notably for making matches and paper where its low flammability makes it safer to use than most other woods.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Shredded aspen wood is used for packing and stuffing, sometimes called excelsior (wood wool).
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Aspen flakes are the most common species of wood used to make oriented strand boards.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] It is also a popular animal bedding, since it lacks the phenols associated with pine and juniper, which are thought to cause respiratory system ailments in some animals.
[src:dodge-aspen/aspen] Heat-treated aspen is a popular material for the interiors of saunas.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The **Dodge Aspen** is a compact car that was marketed by Dodge from the 1976 to 1980 model years.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Deriving its name from the tree and the ski-resort city, the Aspen was the successor to the 1960–1976 Dodge Dart.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Plymouth division sold the model line as the **Plymouth** **Volaré** (Volare = "to fly" in Italian), replacing the Plymouth Valiant.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The model line marked the debut of the all-new Chrysler F platform, which became the ground-up redesign of the Chrysler compact line since its 1960 debut.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] While the two-door coupe lost the hardtop roofline of the Dart/Valiant, the Aspen/Volaré were also offered as a four-door sedan and a five-door station wagon (marking the return of the Chrysler compact wagon for the first time since 1966).
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Aspen and Volaré were both released during a period when the American Big Three were actively downsizing their entire product lines: full-size to compact vehicles were affected.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] As model redesigns reached production, the central factor behind them was reduction of both exterior footprint and curb weight to improve fuel economy, with the industry reclassifying the size nomenclature of existing model lines.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] While considered a compact car upon its 1976 launch, the 1980 Dodge Aspen (otherwise identical in size) was considered an intermediate car (a precursor of the modern mid-size car); it is longer than the full-size LX/LY Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] During its production, the Aspen and Volaré were assembled by Chrysler in its Newark Assembly (Newark, Delaware) and Dodge Main Assembly (Hamtramck, Michigan) facilities; the end of production marked the demise of the latter facility, which closed the same day.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] After the 1980 model year, the Chrysler F platform vehicles were replaced directly with its front-wheel drive K-Cars: the Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré and the Aspen were introduced mid-cycle for model year 1976 as successors to the Chrysler "A-platform" models, the Plymouth Valiant/Plymouth Duster and Dodge Dart.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] During the 1976 model year, Valiant/Duster models were marketed alongside the Volaré at Chrysler/Plymouth dealerships, and the Dart models were marketed alongside the Aspen at Dodge dealerships.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] After the 1976 model year, Valiant and Dart models were discontinued.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Chrysler conceived the Volaré and Aspen as modern, fuel-efficient cars, more luxurious than their Valiant and Dart predecessors.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] They were together named Motor Trend Car of the Year for 1976, and they were noted by *Consumer Reports* magazine for their modern design and good performance.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré and Aspen ultimately suffered numerous quality problems, frequent product recalls, and early rust damage that seriously damaged the cars' reputation and sales.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] During development, the Volaré/Aspen models were extensively wind-tunnel tested to improve their aerodynamics, reduce wind drag and improve fuel economy, improve crosswind stability, reduce wind noise, and increase interior ventilation performance.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The testing led designers to soften the front end contours and remove roof-drip moldings, and at the same time improve internal airflow ducting.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] A reduced number of steel stampings offered improved panel fits with fewer welds.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Larger glass areas increased visibility, with a total glass area increase of 25% on two-door models and 33% on sedans.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The new torsion bar system, though not geometrically as favorable as its predecessor, saved space and weight — as was marketed as giving a "big car ride" with a softer, fore-and-aft compliance.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] This allowed the wheels to move rearward, instead of straight up and down, when the tires encountered an object, thereby dampening the blow and "rolling with" the bump rather than resisting it.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The two transverse torsion bars were mounted along with an anti-sway bar forward of the front wheels, integrating both into a spring-strut front suspension.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] These components were attached to a K-shaped structural cross member, which itself was isolated from the unitized car body by four rubber mounts.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The steering column was also rubber-isolated.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Wheel alignment adjustments such as caster and camber could be made by removing plates over the wheel housings.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Chrysler Corporation also employed the Isolated Transverse Suspension System with their M- and J-platform models.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The rear suspension of the Volaré/Aspen was more traditional for Chrysler passenger cars, using a conventional leaf spring (semi-elliptical) suspension system.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] However, this leaf spring arrangement was also rubber-isolated, which eliminated a metal-to-metal path through which road noise or vibration could be transmitted to the body.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Several 1976 Dodge Aspen sedans served as test vehicles for a gas turbine engine installation, in a project sponsored by the United States Department of Energy.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] This new turbine engine was a smaller version of Chrysler Corporation's earlier turbine engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] At the time, the hope was that turbine engines would be cleaner and more efficient than comparably powerful V8 engines, but numerous technical challenges eventually ended automotive turbine engine development.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] "Ham" Schirmer, manager of Dodge car and corporate advertising for Chrysler, the "Aspen" name originated from the codename "Aspen-Vail" when development for it and the Plymouth "sister car" began in 1971.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Actor Rex Harrison served as pitchman in an advertising campaign for the Dodge Aspen that was inspired by the "Ascot Gavotte" scene in the 1964 movie *My Fair Lady*, which starred Harrison.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In TV and radio advertisements, Harrison performed a patter song using the word "unbelievable" spoken in rhythm.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The "Volaré" name is Spanish for "I will fly away" or "I will blow away"; it is also Italian for "to fly".
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In print and broadcast media, singer Sergio Franchi was featured in Volaré advertisements.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Franchi sang the pop song "Volare", with altered lyrics, in TV and radio commercials for the car.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] As replacements for the venerable Plymouth Valiant and Dodge Dart, the Volaré/Aspen twins shared the same engine and transmission choices and three-box body style with their predecessors, but not much else.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Available as a four-door wagon, four-door sedan or a two-door coupe, Volaré/Aspen models came in three trim levels: The base model, the "custom" (for both models), and the "Premier" for the Volaré and "SE" (special edition) for the Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In their introductory year, the Volaré and the Aspen differed only in their rear taillight styling, front grill and parking light location, and location of their side trim strips (lower for the Volaré, higher for the Aspen).
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Their interiors were completely identical and lacked any kind of branding or differentiation as it was not possible to tell from inside the car whether it was a Volaré or an Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Body styles, engine and transmission options, colors, trim options, and other features were identical.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Coupes featured frameless door glass but—likely to improve rollover safety—a thick "B" pillar was used, replacing the popular hardtop body style of the Valiant and Dart.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The "performance" packages (*Road Runner* for the Volaré, *R/T* for the Aspen) were available only on two-door models; they featured mostly trim items and heavy duty suspension systems.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The standard engine was Chrysler's 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant six, and was available with a single-barrel carburetor.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Optional engines were a 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 or a 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8, both with two-barrel carburetors.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The second model year for the Volaré/Aspen was mostly a carryover, but there were some significant changes.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The standard 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-six engine was supplemented by an optional "Super Six" version that employed a two-barrel carburetor; this setup had previously been available in Australian and Latin American markets roughly ten years prior.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Along with improved performance, this option also helped with the poor drivability problems that plagued the 1976 models.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] A new T-top removable roof panel option was available for the coupe.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Plymouth Volaré was Canada's top-selling car this year.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The trim line arrangement was changed for 1978.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Instead of having separate base, custom, and high-line Volaré premier/Aspen SE models, there was simply the base model, to which the buyer could add custom and premier/SE option packages.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] For their third production year, the Volaré and Aspen received their first visual update in the form of new front grille and fascia treatments.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Starting with the 1978 model year, the standard three-speed manual transmission was no longer available with its shift lever mounted on the steering column; both the standard three-speed and the four-speed overdrive transmissions were only available with their shift levers mounted on the floor.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] New performance and trim packages for both models included the "kit car" and the "Super Coupe", which combined performance trim with the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8, but the six-cylinder engine was standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré or Aspen "kit car", made in honor of NASCAR legend Richard Petty, was supposed to look as much like a race car as possible.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The wheels had no hubcaps, the wheel opening flares had a bolted-on look, and even the windshield had metal tie-downs just like the race cars.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Unlike a race car, the kit car came standard with an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] A special addition was a decal kit with large door mountable "43" decals and "360" decals for the hood.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] These decals were shipped in the trunk either to be installed by the dealer or by the owner.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] It was available in blue for the Volaré or red for the Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Only 131 Dodges and 145 Plymouths were built.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré and Aspen Super Coupe packages (order code A67) included GR60x15 Goodyear GT radial tires on 15x8-inch wheels, Code "E58" 360CID 4bbl engine, x727HD transmission, heavy-duty suspension with a rear sway bar.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The appearance was altered drastically from a standard Aspen/ Volare by adding Matte Black finishes on the entire hood, top of fenders, half the roof, both bumpers and misc. other trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Along with that Blacked out look were full Matt Black wheel well flairs giving a widebody appearance along with a front spoiler attached to the front flairs.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] A 3-piece trunk tail spoiler was also included.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Each were offered as a design package leaving no choice of paint colors.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] All Dodge Aspen versions were Sable Tan Sunfire Metallic (a rich Dark Brown) with orange, blue and yellow stripes to separate Body color from the Black.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Volaré versions were all painted Crimson Sunfire Metallic (a Maroon/Red) with its own special three-color stripes in Yellow, Orange and Red separating the body color from the Black.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Only 494 Volare and 531 Dodge Super Coupes were built.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Wider tail light lenses with amber turn signals replaced the previous all-red lenses on Volaré and Aspen coupes and sedans.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] For the 1978 model year, sales were down over 30% from 1977; total production came to 166,419 (Aspen) and 217,795 (Volaré).
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The only visible difference was the replacement of the amber rear turn signals with red ones.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] For the Volaré, a new coupe-only "Duster" trim package mirrored the Aspen "Sunrise" package, consisting primarily of rear strobe stripes, pinstripe and louvered rear windows, as well as plaid seating, different color options and a "Duster" badge on the Volaré.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The 1978 option packages continued into 1979, with the exception of the super coupe and kit car options.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] A federally-mandated maximum 85 mph (137 km/h) speedometer, new colors, and a diagnostic connector for the engine were added.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Station wagon models were available with a "sport package" (Volaré) or as a "sport wagon" (Aspen) with special stripes, a front air dam, and wheel arch flares.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] For its final year of production, and at the insistence of Lee Iacocca, the Volaré and Aspen were restyled.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] They gained new front styling (very similar to the Ford Fairmont) with a thin grille and rectangular headlamps.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] This was achieved by sharing the hood, fenders, and front bumper with the Dodge Diplomat.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Premier and SE packages were available, but now only available on the sedan and coupe.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré Duster trim package was also available for the 1980 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The R/T package was installed on 285 Aspens for this year.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 was dropped for 1980, leaving the 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 as the top engine choice.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Power from the 318 V8 engine was reduced from 140 hp (104 kW; 142 PS) at 4,000 rpm to 120 hp (89 kW; 122 PS) at 3,600 rpm in two-barrel models.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Four-barrel versions of the 318 V8 saw their output increase from 140 hp (104 kW; 142 PS) (non-California) at 4,000 rpm to 155 hp (116 kW; 157 PS) at 4,000 rpm.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant six engine remained the base engine offering.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Super Six two-barrel carburetor option was dropped, leaving only the single-barrel, Holley 1945 carburetor for the venerable slant six engine.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In this configuration, the slant six produced 90 hp (67 kW; 91 PS) at 3,600 rpm.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Total production came to 67,318 (Aspen) and 90,063 (Volaré), though a significant portion of the sales were for fleet (police and taxi) use.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Plymouth Volaré Road Runner and the Dodge Aspen R/T coupes were the "performance" trim levels of the Volaré/Aspen models.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] They came with E70x14 tires, "rallye" wheels, a grille blackout treatment, body striping, and identifying decals and medallions.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The R/T also made a 60 to 95 mph (97 to 153 km/h) run in 13.8 seconds.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The 225 Slant 6 and both the 318 and 360 "LA" V8s were not available with the four-speed overdrive transmission, only Chrysler Corporation's Model 727 three-speed automatic transmissions were standard.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré/Aspen twins offered station wagon models that became the first domestic compact-sized competition for the AMC Hornet four-door "sportabout" wagon.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré/Aspen wagons also featured a liftgate with a fixed rear window, rather than the more typical drop-down tailgate with roll-down rear window.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The new models had cargo volumes of 71.9 cubic feet (2.04 m3) and load capacities of 1,100 lb (500 kg), which was only 100 lb (45 kg) less than the intermediate and standard size Chrysler wagons.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The liftgate opening was nearly 4 ft (1.2 m) wide and 27.6 in (70 cm) high.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] With the rear seat folded down, the cargo area was 74 in (190 cm) long at the beltline and 43.2 in (110 cm) wide between the wheelhouses.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Side covers of the cargo area were made of one-piece injection molded polypropylene.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Covered, lockable stowage compartments of 1.5 ft3 (42 dm3) capacity were provided in these panels; these compartments were standard on the Volaré Premier and the Aspen SE, and optional on the low-line wagons.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Top-trim Volaré Premier and Aspen SE station wagon models featured simulated woodgrain on its exterior side panels.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Volaré Premier wagons trimmed the "woodgrain" side panels with stainless steel frames accented in matte black; Aspen SE models offered frames that were simulated blond (painted metal) wood-look trim.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Aside from the brand badging and grilles unique on each brand, this station wagon trim element remains one of the few visual clues that differentiated the Volaré from the Aspen.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Production of the Aspen/Volaré ended at the beginning of 1980 with the final vehicle, a Silver Metallic 1980 Aspen equipped with the R/T package (the 285th and final one equipped with said package for this model year), rolling off Dodge Main Assembly on January 4.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] This was also the final car to be produced at the facility, which was closed the same day (its closure having been announced months prior in 1979).
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The car was purchased by Bob Nellis, an electrical contractor for Chrysler.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] It remained in the Nellis family ownership for 37 years before it was sold at the end of 2017.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] After Dodge Main's closure, the site was purchased by General Motors in 1981, after which the factory was demolished to make way for the new Detroit/Hamtramck Assembly, opening in 1985.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Between 1977 and 1979, the small Swiss specialty automaker Monteverdi built 20 modified versions of the Volaré/Aspen called the Sierra to compete in Europe's luxury car market.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The "Dart" name (rather than "Aspen") was applied to Dodge-branded F-platform cars in Mexico and Colombia, corresponding to the local Chrysler-branded F-platform cars badged as "Valiant Volarés".
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] F-body Volaré models were not marketed under the "Plymouth" brand in Mexico because that brand was dropped after 1969.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] During 1981 and 1982, Dart coupes built for the Mexican market used an M-platform Diplomat coupe that was fitted with a 1980 Volare header panel.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Chrysler de México also sold less-expensive versions of the American K-cars: The Plymouth Reliant and Dodge Aries (in 1982–1987) and Plymouth Caravelle (1988) as "Chrysler Volarés".
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The 1988 Chrysler Volaré E (an inexpensive version of the 1988 Plymouth Caravelle modified with a 1986–1988 Plymouth Reliant front end) served as Mexican Highway Patrol units from 1988 to 1990.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] They used Chrysler Turbo II 2.2 L engines and three-speed automatic transmissions (arm shifter on the steering columns, like U.S. patrol cars).
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In Mexico, they were known as "turbo-patrols".
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré also became known as the "Volaré Duster" in Canada.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Volaré/Aspen were recalled numerous times; for the 1976 model year, there were at least eight serious recalls alone.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Chronic problems with stalling and poor drivability led to a horrible reputation that the Volaré/Aspen quickly gained as new buyers were to discover for themselves; premature rusting problems soon followed.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In 1977, 1,300,000 Chrysler Corporation models were recalled for these drivability problems.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] This reputation for poor-build quality led to a decline in sales as the Volaré/Aspen twins became the most-recalled automobile models to that date.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] Winners of the Motor Trend *Car of the Year*, the Aspen and Volaré later received the *Lemon of the Year* award from the Center for Auto Safety, the consumer watchdog group founded by Ralph Nader.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] In 1980, the Volaré/Aspen cars were replaced with the front-wheel drive Plymouth Reliant and Dodge Aries for the 1981 model year.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] However, a new class of the F-platform emerged as the M-Body vehicles that included the Dodge Diplomat and Plymouth Gran Fury four-door sedans, which were very similar in structure, size, and engineering with the Aspen and Volaré.
[src:dodge-aspen/dodge-aspen] The Aspen model name was revived in 2007 for the Chrysler Aspen luxury sport utility vehicle (SUV).
